<HEAD>Spider Mites Threaten Drought-Stressed Soybean Crops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drought-weary farmers who are pinning their hopes on soybeans now face another threat: tiny, hungry mites that like dry weather and can go unnoticed while destroying crops. State agriculture officials say spider mites are invading soybean fields in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and other drought-plagued <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> states. `` It's a difficult critter to fight because they're hard to see with the naked eye,'' said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Landis </PERSON>, a field crops entomologist at <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` When a crop looks bad, it's blamed on other things _ mostly the drought. It's not until the problem becomes severe that the mites are discovered,'' <PERSON> Landis </PERSON> said Monday. The mites, which thrive in dry, hot conditions, feed on the underside of plant leaves by piercing plant cells and extracting the sap, <PERSON> Landis </PERSON> said. After a few days, the leaves bear yellow speckles and eventually turn brown or bronze. `` Entire fields can be completely lost if spider mites are not controlled and weather conditions allow them to build up populations,'' <PERSON> Landis </PERSON> said. The eight-legged pests are easily carried on the wind from field to field. `` It's just another thing you've got to fight,'' said farmer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION>, who recently discovered mites in his soybean field. The infestation is potentially another serious blow to farmers who have lost much of their corn crop in the drought and were hoping to cut their losses with soybeans, which are bringing in higher prices. Because farmers in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> also are combating the mites, there has been a shortage of pesticides to kill the pests, <PERSON> Landis </PERSON> said. `` We are running at capacity in an attempt to meet the stepped-up demand,'' <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrick </PERSON> said of the production of one such pesticide, <ORGANIZATION> Lorsban </ORGANIZATION> 4 E. `` The demand has been so great for the product we're just running out of product.''
</TEXT>
