<HEAD>On the Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILLBURY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A distaste for turning lambs into chops has transformed a sewage treatment plant into a haven for sheep, chickens, geese, rabbits and, as their keeper puts it, `` whatever people throw over the fence.'' The creatures live on the 107-acre spread of the <ORGANIZATION> Upper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blackstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pollution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abatement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> amid tanks, pipes, pools, pumps, an incinerator and plenty of grass for grazing. <PERSON> Emil </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, plant director, recalls that in the spring of 1978 a farmer was allowed to leave two lambs there to fatten up on the plant's grassy field. By the time the farmer returned in the fall, plant employees had grown attached to the lambs and pleaded that they be spared their fate as shish kebab. So, the sewage district board voted to buy the sheep from the farmer. Soon, more creatures arrived unannounced, apparently abandoned by their owners. `` We'd come in the morning and one day we had 12 geese,'' <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said Monday. `` The next day we had 12 ducks, then four chickens.'' On Monday, the `` community,'' as <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> describes it, included three sheep, two dozen geese, two dozen chickens and roosters _ `` we get a lot of roosters'' _ and uncounted rabbits and pigeons. The animals drink from a fountain that carries clean water. They also have the run of two huts, and staff at the sewage plant feed them grain. Motorists stop every day to look, <ORGANIZATION> Holland </ORGANIZATION> said, and some leave with a pet. `` We give them away to anybody who asks,'' <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said, `` as long as they're not going to eat them.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State officials wanted a big check from <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourre </PERSON> for back taxes, and that's what they got. <PERSON> Bourre </PERSON> handed then a check measuring 7 inches by 14 inches, or more than twice the standard size. `` It's a perfectly legitimate check,'' said <PERSON> Bourre </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, resident and a opponent of a <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> law that requires him to pay <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> income taxes because he works at the <ORGANIZATION> Portsmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>. The shipyard is on an island in the <LOCATION> Piscataqua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and is connected by a bridge to <LOCATION> Kittery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> state Treasurer <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> agreed that the check, printed on thick brown paper, was legal tender. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>'s deputy, <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stickney </PERSON>, deposited the $ 981.12 payment in a bank Monday afternoon. <PERSON> Bourre </PERSON>, 40, said Monday that a friend arranged for a printing shop to blow up a check. He said he wanted to make it 4 feet by 8 feet, but `` that's the biggest I could get made up right away.'' <PERSON> Bourre </PERSON> said he had withheld payment during a legal challenge by shipyard workers. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to hear the case.
</TEXT>
