<TEXT>
 Turning the lights on for the first night game at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Wrigley Field is forcing country music's Statlers quartet to change the lyrics of their 7-year-old song `` Do n't Wait On Me. The lyrics of the 1981 song contain the phrase, `` When the lights go on at <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, I'll be coming home to you.'' Although the recording, from the album `` Years Ago,'' ca n't be changed, the group will substitute the line with, `` When they put a dome on <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, I'll be coming home to you'' in performances. `` That ought to keep us ahead of them for a few years,'' The Statlers' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> said from his home in <LOCATION> Staunton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` It never crossed our minds that one day they would put lights in <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, a baseball buff who wrote the song with his brother and fellow group member, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>.
