<FIRST>r a PM-MagazineSecurity     08-09 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Magazine Security,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nervous Over Business Week Scandal, Competitors Watch Their Backs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Insider trading on stolen Business Week stock tip columns has alarmed the magazine's rivals, compelling some to review their own security and recheck back issues to make sure they have n't been victimized, too. `` We do n't take any pleasure in what happened to Business Week, but we're in the enviable position of bolting the barn door before the horse escapes, or at least checking the locks,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Belis </PERSON>, spokesman for Fortune, which has a biweekly circulation of 755,000. `` We're checking the locks.'' <PERSON> Belis </PERSON> said a spot check of Fortune's `` Companies to Watch'' column going back several months showed no unusual prepublication activity in any stocks mentioned. Senior editorial officials at Forbes and Money, two other widely read business magazines, also said they were reassessing protection of market-sensitive material in the aftermath of the scandal at Business Week. In addition, the printing companies used by all four magazines said they were scrutinizing security and reminding all employees that unpublished material is sacrosanct and not to leave the plant. The scandal surfaced July 21 when Business Week, the nation's largest business weekly with a circulation of nearly 1 million, disclosed evidence of possibly illegal trading on stocks featured in its `` Inside Wall Street'' column before it was available to the public A major investigation has since revealed workers in two plants run by Business Week printer R.R. <ORGANIZATION> Donnelley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> took copies the day before they were released to the public and peddled them to brokers, sometimes for as little as $ 20 each. As of the weekend, four <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON> printers and three stock brokers, one each from <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Advest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had lost their jobs. Trades in several more brokerages are under investigation for possible links to prepublished `` Inside Wall Street'' tips. Unlike newspapers, where the time gap between writing and printing sensitive material is brief, weeklies and monthlies face the problem of protecting potentially market-moving items over a period of days and weeks. The problem is compounded in mass-circulation magazines, which rely on printing plants at several locations and the honesty of hundreds of printers, couriers, truckers and postal workers who have access before subscribers do. `` There's a real limitation on our ability to place guards on every truck,'' said <PERSON> Landon </PERSON> <PERSON> Y. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, managing editor of Money, a monthly with a circulation of 1.8 million. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said Money sent a letter to its printer, <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Color </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Effingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, after the Business Week scandal surfaced, warning that `` the material they handle is property of Money magazine. It is their obligation to protect Money's property as it passes through their hands.'' He said a check of Money's `` Wall Street'' column and other potentially sensitive material going back at least one year found no suspicious trading. At <LOCATION> Forbes </LOCATION>, also printed by <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Color </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, deputy managing editor <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Minard </PERSON> said the 740,000-circulation weekly and its printer historically have had a firm understanding about confidentiality. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Minard </PERSON> said, `` we did reiterate to World Color that we expect the agreement we've had with them to be vigilantly observed.'' <PERSON> Minard </PERSON> said there was no effort at Forbes to recheck back issues, but he said, `` I suppose on a continuing basis, I very unofficially monitor it.'' For their part, <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON>, World Color and <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Wauseca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, which prints Fortune, have undertaken security crackdowns. Besides dismissing employees implicated in the Business Week scandal, Chicago-based <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON> has reminded all workers of a ban on removing any material from plants. Others have done likewise. <PERSON> Donnelley </PERSON> also has uniformed sentries at exits, plainclothes guards patrolling production lines and a policy that workers' clothing may be searched Nevertheless, spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratcliffe </PERSON> said, the company still must largely rely on employee's integrity. `` To frisk 650 people would be a bit impractical,'' he said.
