<HEAD>President Prods Congress To Move Faster On Welfare Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not moved quickly enough on welfare reform and urban renewal, and he told the nation's governors they've been `` way out front'' on many social issues. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, a former two-term governor of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, used a speech to the governors Monday to tout his `` New Federalism'' policy of shifting more responsibility for social programs away from the federal government and onto the states. Many governors, especially Democrats, have complained that the states can not absorb increasing cuts in federal aid while maintaining services for their citizens. During his speech at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s meeting in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> described his effort as one giving states a `` leadership role.'' `` We have broken the federal government of its compulsion to control every breath the states take,'' he said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, facing a host of last-minute issues on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> as lawmakers draw near a recess for the Republican National Convention, was playing host to Republican congressional leaders at the White House today. In his <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> complained that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not acted on legislation he submitted six years ago, proposing that the most depressed areas of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s cities receive tax breaks to encourage business investment. `` Despite some minor moves last year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> still has failed to pass meaningful enterprise zone legislation,'' he said. `` Not you. Over half the states have gone forward with their own enterprise zones.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said the states have moved more quickly to get people off welfare rolls. `` Welfare reform is another field in which you have been way out front,'' he said. `` Congress today is still debating a welfare reform package _ years after states started taking advantage of the greater flexibility we gave them.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the federal government should not `` merely let the states toss ideas into a suggestion box,'' but that it should `` honor the leadership role the states have to play.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> won compliments from Republican Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, who said the president `` was talking language we understand.'' But Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> gave a political speech designed mainly to help Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the presidential election. The governor's association has said it wants its meeting to be non-partisan. <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said, `` I think it was as political as he could be without stepping out of line.'' Earlier, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> toured a <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Precision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> plant, telling managers and employees he resents talk about the `` Rust Belt'' in the nation's <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` I get a little tired of hearing <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> and other Midwestern cities called the ` Rust Belt' when the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> is n't the ` Rust Belt.' It's the ` Boom Belt.'''
