<FIRST>r w PM-TurtleSoup     08-09 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turtle Soup,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Danish Film Rouses Friends of Turtle</HEAD>
<HEAD>By CARL HARTMAN</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friends of the endangered sea turtle are upset because a prize-winning Danish film, `` <PERSON> Babette </PERSON>'s Feast,'' has turtle soup on the menu. They are investigating a report from a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> restaurant that it got some sea turtle meat from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> for use in a dinner to promote the film. `` There's a gelatinous substance called calipee under the shell of the sea turtle that's the basis for turtle soup,'' explained <PERSON> Marydele </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON>, director of the Sea Turtle Rescue Fund, in a telephone interview Monday. `` Actually, the turtle you see beating its flippers in the film seems to be a loggerhead, which is a different species that does n't have the calipee,'' she said `` But both are on the endangered species list and its illegal to catch them in this country.'' The film is based on a short story by Danish writer <PERSON> Isak </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinesen </PERSON>, pen name of the late <PERSON> Baroness </PERSON> <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Blixen-Finecke </PERSON>, who also wrote `` Out of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' `` <PERSON> Babette </PERSON>'s Feast'' tells of a Frenchwoman living on the coast of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> who spends her lottery winnings on a big dinner for the villagers who have befriended her in her long exile. The Motion Picture Academy awarded it an Oscar as the best foreign film of the year. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane-Zucker </PERSON>, who is helping promote the film for <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Classics </ORGANIZATION>, said its food consultant has worked up substitute recipes using shitake mushrooms and chopped breast of duck. About 90 restaurants have been interested in reproducing the seven-course meal, he said. Ms. <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> said some restaurants are using diamondback terrapin, which is not a sea turtle but is found in estuaries and considered endangered in some places. Ms. <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> says 10,000 terrapin a year are sold in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> fish markets and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turtle </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tortoise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> is trying to get it put on the state's endangered list Groceries sell a `` mock turtle soup,'' which she says is made from land turtles. They are not on anyone's endangered list, but she would prefer nobody ate turtle soup at all. `` Turtles in the Soup: Recipe for Disaster'' is the title of an article written by Ms. <PERSON> Donnelly </PERSON> for the August issue of `` CEE Report,'' published by the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, sea turtles were n't faring well in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, where the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation to bar the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration temporarily from carrying out a plan to require shrimp fishermen to use devices to protect the reptiles. Turtles often drown when snared in shrimp nets. The bill, sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by voice vote, would prohibit the mandatory use of so-called turtle excluder devices before Sept. 30, a month after excluder-device regulations were slated to take effect. The delay would give <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators time to work out differences in their versions of legislation to reauthorize the Endangered Species Act. Both bills would prohibit the required use of excluder devices in inshore waters until May 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill also would ban device regulations for offshore waters until next May.
</TEXT>
