<HEAD>Neighbors Love, Hate First Night Game at Wrigley Field</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with game rained out, arrest
total. Picks up 7th graf pvs `I think...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Baseball after dark dawned Monday at <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, the last major-league ballpark with day-only games, but rain put out the lights early. The first night game in the 74-year history of <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, between the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phillies </ORGANIZATION>, was delayed by a downpour in the bottom of the fourth inning. It was officially postponed two hours, 15 minutes later, wiping out the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION>' 3-1 lead, since the game will have to be replayed. <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> led off by hitting a home run into the left-center field seats of <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, which for 40 years had been the sole major league ballpark to hold out against lights. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> fans' mood brightened, however, after the home team came back with a first inning homer by <PERSON> Ryne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandberg </PERSON>. The Cubs, mired in fourth place in the National League East Division, scored two more runs before thundershowers forced a delay. `` God is talking,'' said 26-year-old <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>, who had just fled the stadium. `` He does n't want night games at <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>.'' Authorities reported at least five arrests through the rain delay, including three for ticket scapling and two vendor violations, but few other problems, except for illegally parked cars. Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> toured the surrounding <LOCATION> Wrigleyville </LOCATION> neighborhood before entering the park and predicted that residents, some of whom equate Cubs baseball with daylight, would get used to night games. `` I think as we advance the whole plan and get people used to night games I'm optimistic it will eventually smooth out,'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> said. `` It's a historical moment, but it disturbs me because I do n't want people to use my gangway as a bathroom or throw bottles in my alley,'' said <PERSON> Carmelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, 32, a <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> neighbor painting his fence Monday afternoon `` We live here and the people in this neighborhood take care of it. But some fans just do n't respect the community,'' he said. Even President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was struck by the history of the moment. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, boarding Air Force One in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> on Monday, was asked what he thought of the first night baseball game at <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>. `` I'm too old-fashioned,'' said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who early in his radio career did re-enactments of Cubs' games for stations in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. `` There's nothing like daytime baseball. But I understand the need for lights _ box office.'' <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> police scheduled 172 officers, including mounted police and canine units, and revved up 15 tow trucks for illegally parked cars. The normal phalanx for day games is about 50 police, said Officer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kernan </PERSON>. Permit parking is available only for residents of the neighborhood of turn-of-the century, two - and three-flat apartments that is becoming upscale from its working-class roots Outside the park Monday, the excitement began early. Throngs of fans _ some of whom had been there since 8 p.m. Sunday for the best of the general admission bleacher seats _ lined the streets, while T-shirt vendors hawked homemade wares. Some of the parking lot operators near the park put up new prices, $ 15 in one case. Ivy-covered Wrigley Field held on to daytime-only baseball decades longer than any other ballpark in the nation, joining the fraternity of the illumined 40 years after the last team to light up _ the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> voted in February to lift the ban on lights, and lights are scheduled to burn brightly in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> stadium seven times this season and 18 times next season. The $ 5 million lighting system has already added a modern flare to the blue and white <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, which was built in 1914 to house the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Whales of the short-lived <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. There were more than a few attempts to pull the plug on lights even before 91-year-old Cubs fan <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> could throw a ceremonial switch to illuminate the field for the first time. The <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, announced soon after it bought the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 that it intended to put lights in the ballpark, saying day-only baseball cost the company revenue from televised night games. But <LOCATION> Wrigleyville </LOCATION> residents took on the media company and managed to keep the ban on lights alive for almost seven years. <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baseball </ORGANIZATION> in the Sunshine _ <ORGANIZATION> CUBS </ORGANIZATION> _ spearheaded efforts that included lobbying city and state officials. The group decried problems with rowdy crowds, traffic and parking it said would accompany night games. <ORGANIZATION> CUBS </ORGANIZATION> planned to monitor the neighborhood Monday for material to use in a planned court action to limit night games, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, the group's vice president. <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> refused to give details of the court battle, but said it would begin Wednesday. The end of an era also brought out the entrepreneur in some neighbors. `` My mom rented out our roof to some suburban rich people,'' <PERSON> Junior </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, 19, said Monday afternoon at his home across from the ballpark. `` She's even got a gate around the top so if they get drunk they wo n't fall off the side.''
