<FIRST>r w PM-FairHousing     08-09 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fair Housing,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Sends Fair Housing Bill to Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fair housing bill, the first major expansion of civil rights laws in two decades, is heading to the White House for the signature of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who has endorsed the measure. The legislation gives federal officials new power to enforce fair housing laws and extends anti-discrimination protection to the disabled and families with children. The bill was approved Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with no debate. Final congressional passage came in a nearly deserted chamber as a few <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members concurred by voice vote in amendments approved last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The original fair housing law, passed in 1968 after the assassination of civil rights leader <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, gave the federal government only a mediation role in settling housing disputes. Under the new bill, the secretary of housing and urban development is empowered to go to court to seek stiff fines against property owners accused of discrimination. Current protections against racial and sexual discrimination are extended to the handicapped and to families with children under 18. In addition, the bill says new residences with at least four units would have to be accessible to the handicapped. The added protection for families with young children effectively ends `` adults only'' restrictions, except for exemptions for retirement communities for the elderly.
