<SECOND>PM-GOP Rules,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Drops Plan To Give National Party More Authority Over State
Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republicans may have to wait until the 1996 election to break the ties that bind their party to following the wishes of state legislatures controlled by Democrats. A GOP panel on Monday dropped a proposal to give the national party more centralized authority, a notion that makes many Republicans squeamish because that's how the Democrats operate. The decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, if left standing by the convention next week, means the party's current system for picking national convention delegates will remain in place through the 1992 presidential primaries and caucuses. `` One way or another, we ought to be masters of our own fate,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION> general counsel who asked for the withdrawal of his proposal to centralize <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> authority. `` I think the Democrats have done a lot of damage to themselves with their rules,'' said <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulton </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> national committeewoman from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> who advocated a rival proposal that would have given state parties the right to overrule state laws governing party procedures. `` I just think to have any kind of national committee or group approving state party rules is the wrong way to go,'' she said. Dropping the two competing proposals was part of a compromise worked out earlier this summer, Ms. <PERSON> Boulton </PERSON> said. Republican rules currently require state parties to adhere to local laws, such as those establishing and scheduling primaries, in picking their national convention delegates. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said the problem with this is `` there are 36 states where we do not control the legislatures'' and thus Democrats are allowed to govern what ought to be matters of internal <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> policy. The issue arose during the 1988 election, when Southern state legislatures controlled by <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> decided to hold their primaries on one day, which became known as Super Tuesday, March 8. Some Republican state parties raised objections but were powerless to do anything more. <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions have said that the parties, not the states, have the final say over their internal operations, including the selection of delegates to presidential nominating conventions. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said that under those decisions, the national parties clearly have the authority to overrule state law, but it is unclear whether state parties can exercise the same authority. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is considering a case dealing with that very issue, but <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said he did not believe the ruling would go in favor of the state parties. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said his proposal was not intended to allow the national party to meddle in state party affairs, but he acknowledged there was a fear it would put the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> `` on the slippery slope to where the Democrats are.''
