<HEAD>Author of `Zorba' and `Last Temptation' Remains Popular in Greece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Novelist <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON>, who created joy of life with `` Zorba the Greek'' and a religious storm with `` The Last Temptation of Christ,'' remains popular in his native land 30 years after his death. His novels sell thousands of copies every year, mainly in Greek but also in English, French, German and Japanese. He is believed to be the most-read writer in modern Greek. `` We have a huge turnover in the half-dozen major <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> novels. ... In Greek he's mostly bought by young people, and then the tourists pick up the foreign language copies,'' said <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dokimakis </PERSON>. He owns a leading bookstore in <LOCATION> Heraklion </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>, the island where <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> was born. <PERSON> Dokimakis </PERSON> said the two most popular novels are `` Zorba,'' an exuberant portrayal set on <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> of a man with a huge zest for life, and `` Last Temptation,'' which presents <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> as a weak, unstable man who doubts his divinity and dreams of making love to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdalene </PERSON>, the reformed sinner. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cacoyannis </PERSON>' award-winning 1963 film version of `` Zorba the Greek,'' starring <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, has become a classic. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s `` The Last Temptation of Christ,'' to be released Friday, has provoked protest and outrage by Christian groups in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Such a reaction comes as no surprise in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The Greek Orthodox Church condemned the book as heretical when it was published in 1954 and nearly excommunicated <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Moustakis </PERSON>, a Greek theologian, said <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> escaped excommunication `` only because the Cretans were so angry they threatened to burn every church on the island if it went through.'' `` There's still a puritan streak in American life that's bound to be offended by the film,'' he added, `` and I'm sure that its release in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> will bring protests from the church.'' The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> also blacklisted the novel in 1954. Italian director <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeffirelli </PERSON> said he would withdraw his `` Young <PERSON> Toscanini </PERSON>'' from the <ORGANIZATION> Venice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> later this month if <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s movie was scheduled to be shown just before or after it. <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> acknowledged strong personal identification with the tormented character of Christ he portrayed, but said the book was an affirmation of faith. `` I am certain that every free man who reads this book, so filled as it is with love, will more than ever before ... love Christ,'' he wrote in the introduction. On <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>, the largest <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> island with a population of 550,000, <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> is a hero symbolizing its tradition of radicalism and defiant independence. He was born in 1883 into a farm family and studied in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. As a young man, he spent six months in a Greek Orthodox monastery on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Athos </LOCATION>, but later embraced a range of philosophies that included Marxism, Buddhism and nihilism, the denial of all meaning in life. <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> turned to novels late in life after completing what he called his life's work, the 33,000-line philosophical poem `` The Odyssey: a Modern Sequel.'' He settled in <LOCATION> Antibes </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, but always had fistful of earth from <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> in his study. When he died in 1957, <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> was internationally acclaimed but embittered by his failure to win the Nobel Prize for literature. He blamed that on the Greek literary establishment. `` He was always an outsider who never got along with the other literary personalities of his day like -LRB- <PERSON> George </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Seferis </PERSON>,'' a Greek poet who won the prize, said <PERSON> Katerina </PERSON> <PERSON> Angeliki-Rooke </PERSON>, a poet. Her family knew <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> well. `` The establishment here still chooses to ignore him,'' she said. `` There's been no serious intellectual study of his work in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>.'' A <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> revival started seven years ago when Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s new Socialist government made him required reading in public high schools. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyriakakis </PERSON>, 15, of <LOCATION> Heraklion </LOCATION> said: `` I love his books, the way he uses the language, the strange words and the great big ideas. He's inspirational.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> keeps official silence on <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON>, but lay religious organizations still describe his work as blasphemous. Many literary critics dismiss his philosophy as naive and his dialect style as exaggerated and self-conscious. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicellis </PERSON>, a novelist, reflected a common view among Greek writers: `` I find <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> hopelessly old-fashioned. His ideas belong in the 19th century and he forces the Greek language into a rigid, unpleasant mold,'' Readers disagree, and enthusiasm for <PERSON> Kazantzakis </PERSON> surmounts social and regional differences. Ms. <PERSON> Angeliki-Rooke </PERSON> said: `` He catches the popular imagination in a way that no other modern Greek writer has done. In a Greek home with only a few books, one of them will surely be a Kazantzakis.''
