<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Republicans spent more than six months feuding over control of the party, and at the end of a four-hour hearing on seating the state's delegation at the national convention, they wanted more time. The <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> GOP, which was overrun earlier this year by dissidents and supporters of television evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, has tried to regroup after local conventions dissolved into shoving matches, bullhorns and allegations of death threats. Moments after the state committee's counsel completed his summation, the attorney for the challengers asked for an additional 10 minutes to present evidence. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contests </ORGANIZATION>, ruled that that the case was closed. But <PERSON> Brant </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON>, chairman of the dissident delegation, stood up and asked to speak as a private citizen whose reputation had been brought into question. The hearing remained closed. The <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been asked to settle challenges to as many as 39 of the 48 delegates from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee-to-be <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won the Super Tuesday primary but backers of <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> have tried to take over the state party. The committee, which ended the hearing after hours of testimony, videotape presentations and boxes of evidence, planned to rule sometime later in closed-door session and will announce its decision when it reports to the full <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. `` What we are engaged in here today is not a petty squabble,'' <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> GOP Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> told the committee. <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> said that this was the `` opening battle in a war for control of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'' by `` zealots'' and `` traditional malcontents.'' However, both <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Patton </PERSON>, the attorney for the opposing side, said the dispute was more complicated than a disagreement over presidential politics. `` The element of <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been greatly exaggerated by the news media,'' said <PERSON> Patton </PERSON>, `` and picked up by the opposition.'' In fact, any decision over seating a delegation from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> will not affect how the state's presidential votes are cast next week at the national convention, but it will determine who casts them. Because <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won the March 8 primary, all 48 <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> delegates are required to vote for him at the national convention, but the delegates themselves are picked through a process of caucuses and conventions. It is in that process where the dissidents made their moves, showing up in sufficient numbers to dominate the caucuses and obtaining a series of court orders to counter attempts by the state party to thwart them. The feud led to fistfights and shoving matches at one congressional district convention and to an aborted state convention where dissidents with bullhorns controlled the floor, shouting down speakers on the podium. `` Any reasonable person would concur in my opinion that I had to adjourn the convention to prevent a riot,'' <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> said of his decision to gavel a close to the May convention. `` There was a clear and present danger of mayhem.'' As evidence, the state party showed a nine-minute videotape that was a montage of television news stories about the district and state conventions. The tape did show shouting and fist shaking at the state convention but it did not show any violence there. <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> said he had been under guard because of a death threat he had received at his hotel room in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga </LOCATION>. The challengers responded with their own videotape of the state convention, showing <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> gaveling the event to order. Later, after motions to replace the chairman, <PERSON> Stuckey </PERSON> gaveled the convention closed. The tape also showed the dissident delegates locked out of the convention hall. The state party spent much of Monday laying out its case, while <PERSON> Patton </PERSON> used much of the dissidents' time to cross-examine the party's witnesses. Either side can appeal the <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to the Credentials Committee of the national convention. The ultimate authority on challenges is the national convention itself.
