 Communist authorities say they will next year introduce an alternative for those who refuse compulsory 18-month military service, making <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> the second East bloc country to offer the option. While general compulsory service would remain in effect, the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION> said Monday, `` in consideration of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s national and international interests, citizens are to be given a choice ...'' In June, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> became the first <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact country to establish an alternative civilian service. Last week, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> official disclosed that 590 conscientious objectors have refused to serve under arms in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> since 1977. <PERSON> Ferenc </PERSON> <PERSON> Szombathelyi </PERSON>, deputy head of department in the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said 40 to 45 young people have been jailed annually for refusing to bear arms `` This practice must be changed now,'' he told the party daily <ORGANIZATION> Nepszabadsag </ORGANIZATION>. At present, people who refuse mandatory military service in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for reasons of conscience or religion are imprisoned for up to five years. However, <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witnesses, members of the Church of the Nazarene and Seventh-Day Adventists are exempted from military service. According to <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION>, the alternative service `` is not to be punitive in nature, nor more attractive than the armed service, and carries no -LRB- material -RRB- advantages.'' `` The substitutory civilian service, the introduction of which will require amendments in the defense law, will be adjusted to the 18-month long regular -LRB- military -RRB