<HEAD>House OKs Bill To Combat Illegal Ivory Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House has approved legislation to bring the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into line with an international agreement to combat illegal trafficking in African elephant ivory. The measure sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by voice vote on Monday would prohibit imports into this country of any ivory taken in violation of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species. That worldwide agreement uses a system of quotas and ivory markings in an effort to regulate the international trade in ivory from African elephants, whose numbers have fallen to an estimated 700,000 from 1.5 million in 1979. The bill would ban importation of raw ivory from any nation without a native elephant population and would prohibit exportation of raw ivory from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
