<HEAD>Hard Bargaining Ahead Now That Cease-Fire Date Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-UN-Gulf
^By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The three weeks of haggling over conditions for an Iran-Iraq cease-fire are omens of hard bargaining ahead as the war foes plunge into the process of peace after eight years of fighting. Diplomats in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> say that while a cease-fire may halt the shooting fairly soon, efforts to keep the guns silent could stretch on for years. It took three weeks for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to win agreement on truce conditions after both sides finally agreed in principle to a cease-fire. Potential problems lie ahead at nearly every stage of the U.N.-mandated cease-fire process and in the peace talks that are supposed to follow. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution 598 calls for both countries to withdraw to internationally recognized borders, to exchange prisoners, and for a commission to decide who started the war. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> do not agree on their borders. Some prisoners may not want to go home. And an inquiry into the war's causes could make both sides unhappy. Most serious of all, mutual distrust built up by eight years of war and threats will make agreements difficult. `` I think it will be a long, protracted negotiation,'' said a European diplomat in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. The war itself began along two disputed portions of a border that <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON>, Persians and their predecessors have contested almost since the dawn of civilization. The two countries remain at odds over the division of the <PERSON> Shatt </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Arab </PERSON> waterway that separates southern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as it flows into the gulf, as well as over a sliver of land on the central border. The Shatt poses little problem to a cease-fire withdrawal. `` You ca n't stand in the middle of the river,'' one diplomat noted.'' But it could be a tangled issue in peace talks. According to a 1975 treaty, which called for free navigation, the border was set in the middle of the waterway. Before that, the border was set on the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> side, giving <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> control. The 1975 treaty was a victim of the war. Diplomats in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> said President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s need to demonstrate victory in the war could make <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> stubborn on the border question. Iraqis have insisted that any truce immediately open the <PERSON> Shatt </PERSON>, their main outlet to the gulf, which was closed soon after <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded in force on Sept. 22, 1980. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> says the war's first land battles took place on Sept. 4 and 7, 1980, when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> shelled Iraqi cities from the <LOCATION> Zayn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> al-Qaws </LOCATION> area which <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> claimed under the 1975 treaty. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> responded by occupying it on Sept. 7. This area will be a point of dispute in peace talks. Diplomats said snags also lurk in the exchange of prisoners. According to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> held about 50,000 Iraqis, while <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had about 13,000 Iranian captives before recent Iraqi attacks. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> claims attacks in the past month netted it 12,000 more Iranian prisoners. Diplomats say Iraqis fear <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> may have killed some Iraqi prisoners _ a discovery that could endanger peace talks. A <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat cited reports of clashes in Iranian camps involving Iraqi prisoners who had come to support <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. Some Iranians held in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have expressed public support of <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON>. Both have reason to fear a return home. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> measure calls for a commission to probe responsibility for the war, a move taken to answer Iranian demands that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> be branded the aggressor. But the composition and tasks given such a group could trigger fierce argument _ especially if the committee's decisions affect reparations. The Western diplomat said the committee could ask who was `` responsible for provoking, initiating and continuing the war.'' He noted that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> could argue that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s threats and shelling provoked the war and that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> continued the conflict for years after <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> called for a halt. A narrower definition might favor <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which dates the war to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s invasion.
