<HEAD>American Mathematical Society Marks Its Centennial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mathematicians gathered here to celebrate a century of advances that have benefitted fields ranging from medicine to business and have seen American scientists rise to the top of the discipline. `` When we talk about mathematics generally 100 years ago it was a thriving enterprise,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, 49, dean of physical science and mathematics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Stony </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>. `` Even so whole new areas have been developed.'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> was one of about 1,300 mathematicians here for a weeklong meeting that opened Monday to celebrate the centennial anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mathematical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` Geometricians who lived 100 years ago would not believe how large the field has become,'' he said. `` It now interacts with all of the sciences, with biology, with business, with medicine, with economics. I think this would surprise people.'' The computer alone has allowed mathematicians to solve problems today that only existed in theory 20 or 30 years ago, he said. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> said the advances in mathematics in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have been remarkable. `` Mathematics had a small number of American mathematicians _ all of them trained in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>. `` Now American mathematics is pre-eminent in the world, having the leadership in many areas of mathematics. People come from all over the world to study here. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is still important but the balance has shifted.'' Mathematics will continue to move further into medicine and biology, and new understandings in physics will allow mathematicians to develop better machines and computers, he said. The society, originally named the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mathematical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, was formed in 1888 by a small group of mathematicians. It moved its headquarters to <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> in 1951. This week's meeting is one of two the society holds each year in conjunction with the <ORGANIZATION> Mathematical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, society spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmay </PERSON> said. Speakers will address issues ranging from computer graphics to the problems of attracting women to the field. Only about 15 percent of the society's 21,000 members are female, Ms. <PERSON> Holmay </PERSON> said. Of the 18 speakers at the conference, only one is a woman. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Uhlenbeck </PERSON>, 46, a mathematics professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, will speak Friday on `` Instantons and their Relatives.'' Instantons are geometric objects discovered by physicists.
