 The Soviet military, complying with the superpower treaty banning medium-range missiles, has begun dismantling transports and launchers for the weapons at a base in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> observers were on hand to look over 18 launchers to be destroyed during August. The first batch of four missiles was blown up Aug. 1 at a test range in the Central Asian republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. The superpowers signed the treaty banning medium-and-shorter range missiles in December, the Soviets promising to destroy 1,752 missiles that have been deployed or are in storage. The missiles, known as SS-20s in the West, have a range of 300 to 3,500 miles. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> account of the operation did not say how long it would take to destroy the weapons, launchers and transports, or how long the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> observers would stay in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>.
