<HEAD>North Korea Demands Urgent Talks On Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> called today for urgent parliamentary talks on its demand to co-host the Olympic Games and rejected <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s proposal for preliminary negotiations. The communist <PERSON> North </PERSON> said it would agree to a meeting Aug. 17 to handle logistical arrangements for inter-parliamentary talks on the Olympics and a non-aggression pact. But it rejected a South Korean call for detailed preliminary talks on working out an agenda for full-scale negotiations. `` Time is too short to take the form of holding a preliminary contact and then the full talks under the present condition where 40 days ... are left until the opening of the Olympic Games that must be debated as an urgent agenda item,'' the letter said. The Olympic Games start Sept. 17 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has said it will boycott unless it can co-host the event. The letter from <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyong </PERSON> <PERSON> Sop </PERSON>, chairman of the north's rubberstamp <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said the body wants the first full meeting of both parliaments to be held in its capital of <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> It was addressed to South Korean National Assembly speaker <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chae-sun </PERSON>. The tough North Korean letter, delivered at the border truce site of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>, said just three to five delegates from each side should attend the Aug. 17 meeting rather than the 15-member delegations proposed by <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, which had tentatively accepted a North Korean call last month for legislative talks on the Olympics and a non-aggression pact, wants detailed preliminary talks to set an agenda. It called for the preliminary negotiations this week. South Korean officials believe contacts with the north reduce potential threats to the Olympics and they indicate privately the hope of keeping <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> talking until after the Games. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, on the other hand, still hopes to force <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to agree to co-hosting. If it can not co-host the Games, observers say the north needs an excuse and the failure of non-aggression talks might enable it to blame the south. Most observers believe there is little chance of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> dropping its co-hosting demand and taking part in the Olympics. Such a change would represent a total turnabout after 40 years of bitter rivalry for supremacy between the two sides. The north invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean War and the two sides technically remain at war since no peace treaty was signed when an armistice halted fighting in 1953.
