<HEAD>Safety Officials Call For More Controller Training for O'Hare
International</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crowded skies above <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and basic errors by its air traffic controllers have prompted federal aviation officials to scrutinize operations at the world's second-busiest airport. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on Monday called for a `` back-to-basics'' training program for traffic controllers at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> to counter an unusually high number of controller errors. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials say they also plan a broad review of operations at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>. After a special investigation, the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> recommended that controllers at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> be provided with new and better equipment and that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> find ways to increase controller staffing, reduce peak traffic loads, improve training and develop better quality assurance. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment directly on the recommendations, but said it plans its own review of <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> by a team of agency and industry experts, with a report to be submitted to <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> by Sept. 20. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, the review will go beyond air traffic control questions and will include an examination of the airport's overall operation. More than 50 organizations have been invited to participate in the review, including representatives from the airlines, pilots union, various aviation organizations and the city of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. A spokesman for airline pilots said safety concerns are n't unique to O'Hare `` The thing to focus on is that we have overcrowded skies and an insufficient number of controllers,'' said Capt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Damron </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We recognize the problems,'' he said. `` We are supportive and optimistic about our collective ability to produce some suggestions.'' <PERSON> Damron </PERSON> blamed the troubles on the firing of striking air traffic controllers by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in August 1981. Some have been hired back, but not enough to keep up with the growing demand, <PERSON> Damron </PERSON> said. `` There have not been enough applicants, and they have not been able to produce enough controllers,'' <PERSON> Damron </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> handles an average of nearly 2,200 takeoffs and landings a day. Its 796,939 arrivals and departures last year, were second only to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. Last year <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> handled more than 56 million passengers, more than any other airport. But the airport has been the subject of numerous investigations by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> and congressional committees because of safety concerns. The latest <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigation was prompted by reports in June that controllers had committed 19 operational errors where aircraft had been allowed to fly dangerously close to one another, seven more than during all of 1987. After examining these incidents, <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators concluded that in many cases controllers failed to follow procedures and in a majority of the cases the errors involved a `` breakdown in basic -LRB- air traffic control -RRB- skills.'' The safety board said that in many cases the controllers' performance was affected by `` excessive workload, lack of attentiveness, forgetting, perceptual problems, fatigue, and excessive time on position without a break. The board said it was `` concerned that these controllers, working at one of the nation's busiest terminal radar facilities failed to act in accordance with basic controller standards and principles,'' and it questioned the effectiveness of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s overall quality control program The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> also said it was concerned about excessive overtime among controllers, shortages of controllers and the need for better equipment.
