<HEAD>Guns To Fall Silent; Security Council Meeting On Peacekeeping
Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-UN-Gulf Peace, Bjt
^Eds: SUBs 2nd graf to remove reference to war being deadliest
conflict since World War II. LEAD prospects uncertain. Security
Council goes into open session at 11 a.m. EDT.
^By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As dawn breaks over the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> on Aug. 20, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s guns are to fall silent after eight years of war that have claimed the lives of up to 1 million people. Peace talks to end the deadly conflict will begin five days later in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. `` The restoration of peace will bring to the peoples of both countries victories far greater than those of war,'' Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Monday in announcing the truce. The <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meets today to authorize a 350-man unarmed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force to monitor a cease-fire and troop withdrawals. `` I have been assured by the two parties to the conflict that they will observe this cease-fire in the context of the full implementation of Resolution 598,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s comprehensive peace plan, said <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> `` The governments of the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the Republic of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have also agreed to the deployment of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> observers as of the time and date of the cease-fire.'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> did not announce dates for a troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange or other elements of the year-old <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peace plan. The populations and economies of both <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been exhausted by a war fought with modern weapons but with tactics that harked back to the most brutal campaigns of World War I: set-piece battles, trench warfare, mustard gas attacks, human wave assaults. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> told reporters on Monday: `` I wish to declare my government is prepared to accept the demand of the secretary-general and that of the entire world community to refrain from any military action on land, sea and air, starting today. ... `` Let me express my sincere hope that today's historic announcement will be the first step in the implementation of all provisions of Resolution 598, and the achievement of a just, comprehensive and honorable setttlement, returning peace and stability to all the region,'' he added. Ambassador <PERSON> Ismat </PERSON> <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> told reporters: `` Now we begin the arduous but happy march that begins from here. I am sure it will not be a smooth road, but it will be much more pleasant than fighting and bloodshed.'' The cease-fire agreement was announced after a weekend of feverish negotiations in which <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> gave up its demand for face-to-face talks with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as a precondition to a truce. On July 18, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> abandoned its longstanding insistence that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> be branded the aggressor in the war as a first step toward peace, ending a year-long stalemate in peace efforts. One provision of Resolution 598 will establish an impartial commission to judge responsibility for the conflict, and <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> made it clear <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> hopes this commission will blame <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for starting it. War broke out in September 1980 when <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after a series of clashes along the <LOCATION> Shatt-al-Arab </LOCATION> waterway that separates them. The waterway is <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s only outlet to the gulf. On Monday, the secretary-general's office released a report saying the gulf peacekeeping mission may include a small naval patrol for the waterway, the first time the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has planned to commission a fleet. The report estimates the cost of the unarmed peacekeeping force at $ 74 million for the first six months, of which $ 47 million would be start-up costs. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> will assess its 159 members for the cost of the mission. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said Monday that about 25 nations would send officers to the force to be called the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iran-Iraq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. He declined to name the countries, but said it was unlikely that any of the permanent <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ would send troops. If the cease-fire plan takes hold, as diplomats and observers believe it will, it will be the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>' second major peacekeeping success this year. In April, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s pro-Moscow regime signed a peace accord in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> for the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.
