<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> warplanes today blasted a guerrilla base and a PLO-run radio station, knocking it off the air. Police said at least three guerrillas were killed and 12 wounded in the attack near this southern port city. A police spokesman said six <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> warplanes fired 26 missiles in 14 attacks on a building housing offices and studios of the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> radio and an adjacent guerrilla base southeast of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>. He said the two-hour Israeli attack, the longest in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> this year, began at 10 a.m. The three people killed were at the guerrilla base, police said. The police spokesman said most of the missiles hit the ground floor of the radio station building. An Israeli army spokesman in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> confirmed the raid. He said the station was used to broadcast instructions to Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories, where unrest has claimed more than 200 lives since December. `` The base in southeast <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> was a radio station used for propaganda and incitement broadcasts, and to pass orders for executing terror attacks,'' he said. He spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with military regulations. All the planes returned safely, he said. The police spokesman, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said: `` The ground floor, which is the only visible part of the VOP building, was totally demolished by the first four missiles. `` It seems that the Israelis are trying also to demolish the three underground floors of the radio.'' Palls of thick black smoke billowed from the building and the nearby base, about a half mile south of the Mieh Mieh Palestinian refugee camp on <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>'s southeastern edge. Rescuers in a dozen ambulances and fire engines arrived at the stricken building a half hour after the raid ended and dug into VOP's three underground floors to rescue anyone who might be trapped, the spokesman said. The radio station, according to the police spokesman, was founded early in June and beamed special programs to the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement blared by loudspeaker vans, called for urgent blood donations at <LOCATION> Mieh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mieh </LOCATION> and the nearby camp of <PERSON> Ein </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Hilweh </PERSON>. The police spokesman said the raiding jets fired scarlet balloons to deflect heat-seeking, shoulder-held missiles fired by Palestinian guerrillas. Witnesses in <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said guerrilla defenders firing their anti-aircraft guns missed the raiding jets. One witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said motorists deserted their vehicles and sought refuge in orange and banana groves as the Israeli warplanes roared overhead. He said air raid sirens wailed in <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, the provincial capital of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, during the attack. Shopkeepers lowered their shutters and several people deserted businesses and took cover in basements and bomb shelters. It was the 12th Israeli air attack in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> this year. By police count, 62 people were killed and 81 wounded in the previous 11 raids.
