<HEAD>Gun Attacks, Other Violence Marks Internment Anniversary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with eight police injured, 42
arrests, 80 attacks, clashes outside Belfast, other details. EDITS
to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunmen fired on security forces before dawn today as gangs of <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> supporters took to the streets to mark 17 years since authorities began jailing guerrilla suspects without trial. Eight police officers were injured, none seriously, and 42 people were arrested, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constabulary </ORGANIZATION>, the province's police force. Four injured civilians were still hospitalized today but the exact number treated and released was not known. Police said the gangs launched about 80 attacks on security forces Monday night and early today in a constant barrage of bullets, bombs, rocks and other missiles. Protesters hijacked cars, erected barricades across streets and lighted dozens of bonfires. Security forces fired plastic bullets to break up the rioters, including a crowd of several hundred throwing gasoline bombs at police outside a bus station. On at least one occasion, police opened fire with live ammunition. The violence was concentrated in the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> western and northern areas of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. Outside <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, there was less trouble although clashes were reported in <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armagh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Down </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Downpatrick </LOCATION>, County Down, a primary school was damaged by fire and there were three arrests. In <LOCATION> Antrim </LOCATION>, two houses were set on fire, police siad. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> abandoned internment in December 1975 after worldwide criticism, but <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> supporters continue each year to mark the anniversary of its introduction on Aug. 9, 1971. In separate attacks, shots were reported fired at a police patrol and at a police station and a grenade was thrown at an army barracks. A stolen car crashed t