<TEXT>
 Medical debris like that plaguing beaches in the Northeast has been found on a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> beach and police were investigating reports that more material washed up today, police said. No beaches were closed. Used syringes and vials such as those used in blood tests were found in a plastic trash bag that washed up Monday night at <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said today. `` It has blood vials, testing vials, and some used syringes in it and other medical debris,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. `` I did not detect any blood. I opened the top of the sack up to see what was in it. There were no blood samples or anything ... I did n't see any needles. It appeared the needles had been cut off.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said he was awaiting direction from <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON>, emergency management coordinator for <LOCATION> Carteret </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, about possibly closing beaches. `` We do n't foresee any problems at this time ...,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. Numerous beaches have been closed for varying periods this summer along the coasts of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> because of medical waste and sewage. Because of the high tide, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said he and the police chief of nearby <LOCATION> Pine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Knoll </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shores </LOCATION> were unable to get onto the beach to look at other materials found today. `` All we know is there's some stuff washed up and we do n't know what it contains,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. The disco