<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `Three hours ...,' to CORRECT that rain delay
began two hours, NOT three hours, after lights went on. A version
moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bright lights of night baseball illuminated <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> for the first time in 74 years, but the historic game was cut short when the rain came and lightning bolts lit up the sky. `` I feel like we saw the beginning of history being made, but we did n't get to see the end,'' lawyer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurasch </PERSON> said Monday night, as the heavy rain halted the game in the bottom of the fourth inning with the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> leading the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phillies </ORGANIZATION>, 3-1. Two hours after 91-year-old Cubs fan <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> declared `` Let there be light!'' and threw the switch that turned on the towering <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> lights, the clouds took over. The game at the last major-league ballpark with day-only games was postponed two hours and 10 minutes later, delaying <PERSON> Wrigley </PERSON>'s first official night game until tonight's contest between the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mets </ORGANIZATION> Monday's rain was seen as symptomatic of the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION>' seemingly endless disappointments to its fans, like when the team blew potential championships in 1984 and 1969. `` It's kind of like the fates are against them,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, a neighborhood activist who led the fight against night games. Some made out anyway. Scalpers got up to $ 250 for tickets. Rooftops with views of the field were rented out for as much as $ 1,000. Fans with tickets to Monday night's game can exchange them for any game for which tickets are available or get refunds, the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> said. They wo n't be able to attend tonight's game; it's sold out. The day began with boundless optimism for <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> fans. Throngs filled the <LOCATION> Wrigleyville </LOCATION> neighborhood early, many chugging beer. An army of vendors hawked commemorative T-shirts for up to $ 15 a piece. `` I think it's beautiful,'' said <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, 62 as she sat on the stoop across from <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION>'s main entrance in 99-degree heat. `` It seems like everybody's in a good mood despite the heat. I have n't seen a crabby face yet.'' Some residents prepared for the worst, organizing patrols against drunkeness and vandalism. `` I never minded the day games because it's daylight and you can see what the people are doing, but I mind the night games,'' said <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Habbe </PERSON>, 56, who has lived less than a block from <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION>'s main entrance for 20 years As daylight faded, parts of the neighborhood began resembling a party. On the roof of one apartment building across from <LOCATION> Wrigley </LOCATION>'s right-field wall, 45 peopled attended a catered party where the women wore cocktail dresses and the men black ties, tuxedo tops and Hawaiian shorts About 250 people, many clutching beer cans, gathered behind the left-field wall to watch the lights being turned on and try to catch a home run ball. In their midst, stood <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who drove 300 miles to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Lovington </LOCATION> in central Illinois, even though he was not among the sellout crowd of 39,000 with tickets. `` We just could n't pass this up. This is just incredible. It's a great big party. You can just go from bar to bar to bar,'' he said. Police were prepared with a force of 172 officers, including mounted patrols and canine units, but few problems materialized. Authorities reported at least five arrests, including three for ticket scalping and two vendor violations. And city officials said more than 60 illegally parked cars were towed by the start of the game. Ivy-covered Wrigley, built in 1914, held on to its daytime-only baseball tradition decades longer than any other ballpark in the nation. The last team to light up _ the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> _ did it 40 years ago. <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> voted in February to lift the ban on lights despite fierce opposition from a neighborhood group known as <ORGANIZATION> CUBS </ORGANIZATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baseball </ORGANIZATION> in the Sunshine. The team has eight night games for this season and 18 for every year until 2002. But <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, vice-president of the opposing neighborhood group, vowed Monday night that <LOCATION> Wrigleyville </LOCATION>'s residents wo n't give up their fight, begun in 1981 when the <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> bought the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> and announced its plans to erect lights. If the group fails to halt night games or at least win a curfew and other restrictions, <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> predicted, the <LOCATION> Wrigleyville </LOCATION> precinct would vote the area dry of alcohol in the spring 1989 municipal election. `` I think it would be a real disservice, especially watching this carnival atmosphere, to give up the fight,'' <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON> said.
