<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said today there is no room for further compromise with Republicans on aid to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels because `` we've gone as far as we can go.'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, told reporters he is prepared to press the Democratic aid plan to a vote and continues to hope it will attract bipartisan `` That would send the right message to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said `` we're still hopeful of getting a Contra aid package passed.'' Speaking to reporters not long after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressional leaders, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said `` the Democrats say they want a bill.'' But he also said that `` the language -LRB- of the Democratic bill -RRB- is convoluted.'' Many Republican senators made it clear Monday they do not trust the Democrats to carry out their side of the bargain. They said the Democratic aid plan is seriously flawed because it does not contain adequate resources to deliver stockpiled arms to the Contras and has no guarantee <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> will permit a vote. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> was asked if there was any flexibility on his side of the issue. `` No, I do n't think so,'' he replied. `` It seems to me we've gone as far as we can go. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the administration is concerned about what he called weaknesses in the Democratic bill with respect to systems for getting assistance delivered to the Contras. He said that bill `` would have the impact of saying you can deliver it in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> but not in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, and that's where the troops are.'' Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, speaking Monday after a private meeting in which many Republicans objected to the Democratic plan, said he would take `` one more shot'' at negotiating a bipartisan aid package. However, he added: `` I would n't want to be overly optimistic.'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> also said he hoped some compromise could be reached. But Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, R-Ariz., said compromise was unlikely because the debate over aid to the rebels fighting <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government `` has been so long, so emotional, so partisan, that there's little trust Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., who took part in talks with Republicans on the compromise legislation last week, said flatly, `` The negotiations are over I do n't think there is any more room. We've gone as far as we can go.'' The Democratic plan would permit $ 27.1 million in immediate non-lethal `` humanitarian'' aid to the Contras. It also would give President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> an opportunity to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this fall to release some $ 16.3 million in previously purchased arms, ammunition and other military supplies now stored in warehouses in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. But it also requires <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to certify that such military aid to the Contras is justified because <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has disrupted the `` peace and stability'' of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> by taking two of these three actions: an unprovoked military attack on the Contras, `` blatant violations'' of the regional peace plan, and continued `` unacceptable levels of military assistance by Soviet-bloc countries, including <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.'' Some senators said <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s rulers could prevent the military aid from being released `` just by being good boys for 30 days.'' Conservative Republicans called on <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> to force a vote on a Republican alternative which would make $ 20 million in new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid available to the Contras as well as releasing previously approved military aid from warehouses and providing the `` humanitarian'' assistance. Sources inside the meeting said Army Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s national security adviser, reported that he has `` serious reservations'' about the plan. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said that if progress is not made in reconstructing a bipartisan alliance on the issue, he will offer the Democratic aid plan as an amendment to the pending <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill. Contra leaders contacted the White House and several <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators Monday morning to declare their unanimous opposition to that plan. <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Contra resistance forces, said <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> leaders see the Democratic plan as resulting from `` internal politics in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> which basically seek to reward -LRB- Nicaraguan President -RRB- <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> for not complying with the commitments of the peace process.''
