<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense contractors routinely overcharge the government for spare parts, and the excess charges, although small in percentage terms, total hundreds of millions of dollars, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. An unusually broad internal defense audit found that nearly half the contracts reviewed involved some measure of overcharging. In the majority of instances, the auditors reported, the overcharges resulted from a military contractor's failure to abide by a law requiring the company to share with the government the latest information it has on labor and material costs. If the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> receives `` defective'' cost or pricing data in the course of contract negotiations, the result is almost always an overcharge to the government, the auditors noted. The audit, conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general, took more than three years to complete and was one of the largest ever conducted. It reviewed 774 contracts and subcontracts, worth a combined $ 54.3 billion, held by 95 companies. `` Of the 774 pricing actions audited, 365 -LRB- 47.2 percent -RRB- were overpriced by $ 788.9 million,'' the report said. `` The principal reasons for the overpricing were that contractors did not comply with Public Law 87-653, Truth in Negotiations Act, on 359 of the 774 pricing actions.'' That level of overpricing amounts to slightly less than 1.5 percent of the total value of the contracts audited, the report added. By law, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> can recover money overcharged by contractors, with interest. The government's claims can be contested by the contractors and the disputes resolved through negotiations. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, in releasing the inspector general's audit, announced the department had so far recovered $ 283 million of the $ 788.9 million identified in the report. `` The department will continue to examine all costs questioned and to recommend appropriate actions,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> added. The inspector general concluded his report by suggesting the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> hire more auditors, recommending the department `` provide the funding and resources needed to substantially increase the level of defective price audit coverage provided.'' The report noted that, historically, the audit agency can recover about $ 19 in excess costs for every dollar spent on price audits. That recommendation, however, already has become the subject of an internal dispute. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Helm </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s comptroller, said in comments attached to the report he did not view the findings as adequate justification for the expense of hiring more auditors. He and other <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said the current force of auditors could improve the situation by helping defense contractors devise more accurate methods of estimating costs for use during negotiations.
</TEXT>
