ls, restrict imports to save dollar reserves and control prices of basic consumer goods to fight inflation. He also has announced plans for a more restrictive policy toward foreign investment and, unless creditors agree to easier terms, a moratorium on foreign debt payments. `` I do n't believe the debt is payable under the present circumstances,'' he said recently. Personal animosity between <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> and <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> has created problems in the transition of power. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> said he would not attend the inauguration or follow the Ecuadorean custom of personally turning over the presidential sash to his successor. `` Since the wellfare of the Ecuadorean people depends on the next government, may God help them and insure their success,'' he said Friday. `` But knowing them as I do, I have my doubts.'' Besides the personal feud, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s political turmoil in recent years has included two unsuccessful military rebellions against <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, a kidnapping of the president in which disaffected paratroopers held him for 11 hours, and an attempt by the opposition-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to impeach him. <PERSON> Borja </PERSON> has accused <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> of trying to sabotage the new government by creating economic problems before he takes office. `` We are concerned by the bankrupt state in which we are receiving <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>,'' he said, and charged the <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> administration with creating an 11 percent budget deficit `` to cause us difficulties'' with inflation. Interior Minister <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> described the complaints as `` whining.''
