<HEAD>Bodies of Ferry Disaster Victims Cremated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATIHAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bodies of 10 people who died in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s worst ferry disaster were cremated Tuesday on the banks of the <LOCATION> Ganges </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> as police fired seven gunshots in honor of the more than 400 passengers believed drowned. Hindu and Moslem priests prayed as the bodies were placed on wooden logs and set aflame near the river that Hindus consider sacred. About 1,000 relatives and villagers watched silently. The 35-year-old steam-powered ferry overturned Saturday when it hit a sand bar while crossing the river and hurled at least 542 people into the surging waters about 650 miles east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. About 100 people swam to shore or were rescued by villagers in small boats. Only 30 bodies have been recovered and the rest of the passengers are presumed dead, officials said. Most of the passengers were Hindu pilgrims on their way to a shrine. The government blamed the accident on overcrowding and safety violations, according to officials who spoke on condition of anonymity. The ferry had a capacity of 160. Two steam-powered boats and 70 rescue workers have tried to pull the vessel from the river bed, but the search has been hampered by swift currents and rising water levels caused by monsoon rains. <PERSON> Asgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, who heads the recovery effort, said bodies are believed to be trapped inside the ferry, but none have been found so far. He said many of the bodies were carried away by strong currents. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s worst previous ferry disaster occurred in 1970, when at least 150 people drowned in the <LOCATION> Krishna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in the southern state of <LOCATION> Andhra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION>.
