<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today accused <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of trying to `` run away'' from a record `` on the very, very far liberal fringe'' and said his Democratic rival is losing his lead in the presidential race. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, at a news conference here, predicted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would fall back from the 17-point advantage he has registered in some national polls. `` That is turning around,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` You watch, in the next couple of days you'll see evidence of the turnaround on that.'' He did not elaborate. Just six days before the opening of the Republican National Convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, where he will become the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nominee, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he still has not decided who will be his running mate. `` I'm not close in the sense of like tomorrow making a final decision,'' the vice president said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he wants to keep it a secret until the final day of the convention. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke at an airport news conference here after a speech earlier in Erie. Later, he planned to fly to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> for a ribbon-cutting at the <ORGANIZATION> Polish-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> and to take part in a crime-fighting effort called the `` National Night Out Against Crime.'' Americans in more than 7,200 towns plan to turn on porch and house lights as a symbolic message that they intend to fight for safer neighborhoods. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in his speech, but went after him at the news conference. `` He's trying to run away from a record in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> on the very, very far liberal fringe of the political spectrum, and I have to pin him down and I have to get him to say what he's really for,' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` And he's unwilling to do that because he thinks he can preempt the middle.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was urging speakers the GOP convention to be positive and to focus on the issues. `` But I ca n't guarantee that somebody's not going to take a swipe at <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` I have a lot of friends out there and they did n't like the vicious, personal attacks -LRB- against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the Democratic convention -RRB- and I did not react to them, but I ca n't control everbody but I'm urging them to stay positive, as I'm doing.'' In Erie earlier, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> blamed liberals in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for undermining the battle against illegal drugs and told a gathering of police officers, `` Let's get tougher on the criminals.'' In a speech billed as non-partisan, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by name. But he criticized the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, whose members he has said include <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. He said that to win the war against drugs the nation must be as committed as it was in World War II `` when the whole nation then pulled together, one purpose, one cause, everyone working in exactly the same direction. We've got to plan an attack at every level of government.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke before the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> chapter of the Fraternal Order of Police on his last major campaign trip before the Republican National Convention. Trying to forge an image as a hard-liner on law enforcement, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` When it comes to criminal justice our first priority must be to keep the criminals away from the good and decent people who want to raise their families in peace and safety. `` There are those, like the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>, whose first concerns are the protection of the criminals' rights and the potential abuse of power by police,'' the vice president said. `` My first concerns are the protection of law-abiding citizens and the abuse of our system of constitutional protections by thugs who can go and hire smart lawyers and find the right judges to set them free. `` So let's not take away the guns of innocent citizens,'' he continued. `` Let's get tougher on the criminals.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that too often police are being denied the ammunition they need to fight the battle against drugs. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is full of rhetorical heroes on the issue of drugs, but when it comes to law enforcement a lot of the liberals there go AWOL,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the budget request for the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was slashed by $ 72 million last year in order to provide more money for mass transit and <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, resulting in a 55 percent reduction in <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> air and sea patrols. He also blamed `` the liberals in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'' for derailing sentencing guidelines necessary for implementing a federal death penalty under constitutional standards set by a 1972 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Americans must insist that judges accept new federal sentencing guidelines that mandate consistently tougher penalties. `` We also need to change the legal technicalities that set criminals free,'' he said. `` There's something wrong with the system when the modern-day version of a prison break is crawling through a loophole.'' He praised the administration of former <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, now the attorney general-designate, for reducing by 94 percent the early release of convicted felons in the state and said <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> effectively ended the early release or parole of first-degree murderers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for more money for building prisons and said that unnecessary military bases should be converted to prisons or rehabilitation facilities. He also urged that states that have decriminalized possession of drugs should reverse course. `` And to those who say drugs should be legalized I say this _ legalization is just another word for surrender, and surrender is not in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s vocabulary.'' One day earlier, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s efforts to compat drug abuse, saying, `` Anybody who can raise the consciousness of the young people of this country about staying away from drugs certainly can have a useful role.'' But he made no promises when asked if the former Democratic presidential candidate might have a role in his administration working on the drug issue.
