<HEAD>The Most-Joked-About Candidate: Bush Is the Winner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Whether he wins the November election or not, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is way ahead in one contest: <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> told more jokes about him than any other political candidate in the first half of 1988. <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>'s monologues on `` The Tonight Show,'' considered one indicator of what people outside politics are thinking, were analyzed by <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Amundson </PERSON> and <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON>. The two researchers, who also looked at comedian <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON>'s monologues on `` Late Night,'' published their findings on political humor in the magazine Public Opinion. `` Poor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> endured a veritable comedic vivisection,'' the pair wrote. `` The late-night hosts carved up his record, his campaign tactics and his manhood.'' <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>, on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s speaking ability: `` The last time <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> gave a speech someone came up and drew a chalk outline around his body.'' In <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>: `` I think <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went too far when he stuffed straw in his overalls and started to sing ` If I Only Had A Brain.''' And during Super Tuesday season: `` Down South he went into a truck stop wearing a pair of overalls, but he had a little alligator sewn over the pocket.'' <PERSON> Amundson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON> looked at the <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> monologues from Jan. 1 to June 7. They found that <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> was far more political than <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> and included jokes about at least one candidate in nearly every new episode of his show. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign manager, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, has said he pays close attention to the <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> monologues `` as a barometer of how the candidates play in the ` real' <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> beyond the beltway,'' the highway that encircles <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amundson </PERSON> said. And <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>'s not the only one. `` When <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> talks, candidates have to listen,'' says <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON>. `` They listen to hear what <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is hearing.'' Republican contenders were the butt of <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>'s jokes twice as often as the Democrats, with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the target of 32 barbs followed by <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> with 18 and <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> with 17. On the Democratic side, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> attracted 15 jokes, <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> was the target of nine and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbit </PERSON> drew five. The lower numbers for the Democrats `` reflect the writers strike that put ` The Tonight Show' on reruns during the peak of Democratic campaigning in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' the authors said. `` It certainly does n't mean they were any less laughable than the Republicans.'' The <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> jokes centered on his relationship with model <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, starting in January when <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> remarked that `` <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> made a stunning statement today. He said if he was elected he would not be the first adulterer in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but he would be the best.'' <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON> got into the act, the researchers reported, on the day President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had his annual physical. `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> says he has the body of a 20-year-old _ which if I remember correctly is very much like the <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> campaign slogan,'' the comedian said. <PERSON> Amundson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON> said most of the jokes focused on gaffes and personal foibles, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s appearance and `` the utter hopelessness'' of <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>'s quest. `` I'm not sure if I want a president who has to draw in his face,'' <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said after what the researchers called `` the mysterious appearance'' of <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s eyebrows before the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses. And when <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> endorsed <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> cracked, `` <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> lending support to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is like <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> lending her bra to <PERSON> Oprah </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfrey </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> disputed <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s claim that Planned Parenthood was formed to create a master race. Obviously that's not true, <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> said, or we'd have a better class of presidential candidates. Conspicuously absent from the barrage of quips was Democratic nominee <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a straight-laced candidate. <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Amundson </PERSON> are thinking of continuing their survey through the general election campaign `` just to see if <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> can find something funny about <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.''
