<HEAD>Soviets Inspect Two Sites As Part of INF Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOSSELIES, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet officials Tuesday began counting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles at two sites in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> as part of inspections allowed under the superpower arms treaty. The first team of 10 Soviet inspectors arrived by bus at the European Repair Facility at <LOCATION> Gosselies </LOCATION>, about 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, to check missiles at a maintenance site. They paused for photographs and then went quickly into a one-story building that is part of the operations run by the Belgian defense contractor <ORGANIZATION> Sabca </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a straightforward kind of process,'' said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Findley </PERSON>. `` This is bean-counting, going in and looking at what the treaty says are limited and figuring it out.'' The Soviets, he said, would have a chance to measure unarmed cruise missiles removed from their canisters for repair or maintenance. `` They may take special measurements and check because this is the only place they can do it,'' <PERSON> Findley </PERSON> said. There was no indication how many missiles were at the facility, the only one of its kind in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> set up to maintain and repair the weapons. The number can vary daily. On June 21, there were 55 missiles at the plant, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. A second team of 10 inspectors went to <LOCATION> Florennes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, 10 miles north of the repair facility. Sixteen ground-launched cruise missiles and four spares are kept at the base along with four launchers and eight spares, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The sleek, ground-hugging weapons, which arrived in March 1985, are jet-propelled, winged missiles with advanced guidance systems. They are 21 feet long. The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty provides the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with unprecedented review of each other's facilities. The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and five Western European countries. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts are inspecting 133 sites in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Each inspection can last up to 24 hours, with a possible eight-hour extension. The Soviet experts, who arrived Monday, spent the night in a <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> hotel and notified authorities Tuesday that they wanted to inspect the two sites. They were expected to spend Tuesday night at the facilities and return to <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> on Wednesday. They will leave <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> later Wednesday or Thursday. The Soviets were taken on a two-hour bus tour of the historic capital with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Col. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> MacNamee </PERSON>. He said they expressed interest in the Gothic and Baroque architecture. <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> is the fourth Western European country visited by the Soviet teams since the 60-day inspection process began July 1. They have visited <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. They have yet to inspect sites in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The treaty provides for elimination within three years of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges from about 300 to 3,400 miles. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> signed the treaty in December in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
