<HEAD>For $5, Folks Learn What Their Family Treasures Are Worth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Art appraisers <PERSON> Stacey </PERSON> <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Jelley </PERSON> were in town anyway for an auction of works from two failed banks, so folks at the <ORGANIZATION> Anchorage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> and Art figured they'd use their services for a fund-raiser. For a $ 5 donation to the museum, people were invited to bring in their family treasures Monday and find out from the experts what they were really worth. There were no major finds and a lot of disappointment as the appraisers spent five hours reviewing a host of objets d'art, but a few people learned their pieces were at least good buys. Roman said he mostly examined `` a lot of photo reproductions.. a lot of decorative pieces,'' and said things like, `` It would cost you more to get it framed than it's worth.'' He said he developed the phrase `` decorative piece'' because `` it's better than telling somebody it's a piece of junk. ... Just because it does n't have a lot of value does n't mean it does n't have sentimental value.'' Roman and <PERSON> Jelley </PERSON> work for the California-based art auction house of <ORGANIZATION> Butterfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Butterfield </LOCATION>, and the main purpose of their visit is Wednesday night's auction of a collection acquired by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as a result of its takeover of two failed <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> banks. The collection includes a huge <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Laurence rendition of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION>, valued $ 180,000 to $ 220,000, and some other works valued at more than $ 10,000. `` Literally, it's a treasure hunt,'' Roman said. He is director of the auction house's painting department and his hope was to unearth paintings worth shipping to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for sale. <ORGANIZATION> Butterfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Butterfield charges commissions ranging from 35 percent for items that sell for $ 100 or less, to 10 percent for pieces sold for $ 5,000 or more. `` Basically, my job is to look at beautiful things all day,'' Roman said. And every day hope springs anew that someone will pull out of a plastic bag `` some amazing painting that's never been seen in 100 years.'' But it was not to be Monday. <PERSON> Jelley </PERSON> said he saw `` a nice little rug and a cast bronze bust,'' but the only thing perhaps worth shipping to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> was a silver tea set he plans to research some more. Other items produced included a large parchment page of Gregorian chant, brought back from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after World War II, whose owner believed it dated from the Middle Ages; a Hungarian mirror painting _ a religious scene purchased 21 years ago for $ 20 in a <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> antique shop; and a sealed bottle of Old Mr. <PERSON> Boston </PERSON> <PERSON> Straight </PERSON> <PERSON> Rye </PERSON> <PERSON> Whisky </PERSON> from the Prohibition era. The parchment, it turned out, was probably 19th-century and not worth much. But the Hungarian mirror painting was definitely a good buy. It would probably bring about $ 600 at auction, <PERSON> Jelley </PERSON> told its owner, who had talked her way past Hungarian border guards when they questioned whether she should be allowed to take the painting out of their country. The whiskey too had no value at auction, because while wine can be auctioned off, it is against the law to auction hard liquor. So what are <PERSON> Jorene </PERSON> and Shield Downey going to do with grandma's medicinal pint, preserved so carefully all these years `` Our anniversary is on Valentine's Day,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> said. `` We're going to drink it.''
