<HEAD>Control Board Takes Control Of Yonkers</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MARLENE AIG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state board today assumed control of the city's finances and threatened defiant council members with criminal charges in an effort force them to accept a court-ordered desegregation plan. `` In short, our goal is to save <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> from itself,'' said Secretary of State <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Yonkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The board voted 5-1 to impose a wage and hiring freeze and made council members who refuse to obey rules for fiscal responsibility subject to misdemeanor charges. The four council members who voted against the desegregation plan ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON> already are paying fines and face a threat of imprisonment beginning Thursday on Sand's contempt of court citation. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> today said it would rule on a city request to stay $ 500-a-day fines against the councilmen and bankrupting fines against <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>. The panel did not say when it would rule. The control board, established by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> earlier in the decade when <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> came near bankruptcy, has sweeping powers to control the budget of the state's fourth largest city. It could remove the councilmen from office. City Manager <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON> cast the single negative vote because `` the control board is not strong enough at this time to avert fiscal disaster ... We may have to look to other entities to join me in resolving this issue.'' Mayor <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasiscko </PERSON>, who has called a council meeting for Wednesday night, said, `` The only thing that will make any difference is the threat of removal'' from office. Sand fined the city $ 100 the first day, doubling daily so that by day 22 the amount would have wiped out the city's $ 337 million budget. <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON> said the city would begin mass layoffs if the situation was not resolved by Monday. Sand, who in 1985 found the city liable for intentionally segregating its schools and housing over 40 years, found the city and councilmen in contempt last week when the council voted 4-3 against a resolution supporting the construction of 800 units of affordable housing throughout the city. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sculnick </PERSON>, attorney for the city, asked the appellate panel today to put the fines on hold pending a full appeal of Sand's contempt order because if they continued, `` the city will be bankrupt in less than two weeks.'' Lawyers for the councilmen argued that Sand had exceeded his authority by ordering passage of legislation that would implement the housing plan. `` There are limits to a federal court's authority even to remedy an unconstitutional action,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, attorney for Councilman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON>. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sussman </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assocation </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, contended that the appeals court had a duty to Sand. `` The dignity of the federal court is under assault,'' said <PERSON> Sussman </PERSON>, `` by a group of citizens who think they're above the law. <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON>, who has pinpointed Aug. 21 as the last day the state's fourth largest city can pay the price of defiance, said if the appeals panel denied the stay, he would write to Sand asking him to grant a stay himself and initiate round-the-clock negotiations to resolve the crisis But <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON> said the city has about $ 66 million cash on hand and the last day the city can pay a fine is Aug. 21, when the daily fine is $ 26.1 million, but the cumulative fine would be $ 52.4 million. He said he still hoped <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> would intervene or that one of the councilmen would change his vote. Sand had called for the governor's assistance, noting the governor's power to remove elected officials. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has said he is reluctant to do that because it would be complicated and the city has appealed the contempt finding. Getting a councilman to change his vote would be difficult, too, `` because they're all heroes now,'' said <PERSON> DeLuca </PERSON>. The four, Vice Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON>, may face additional financial pressure if a citizens' group goes ahead and files a $ 100 million civil suit against them for negligence, dereliction of duty, illegal conduct and waste <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON>, an attorney and vice president of Citizens and Neighbors Organized to Protect <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, said the four councilmen had violated state law and the City Charter by their actions and had caused the city irreparable harm publicly and financially.
