<HEAD>Eight Rivers Set Record Lows in July</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng: _The Appalachicola, to CORRECT
spelling of Apalachicola and Chattahoochee</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight drought-plagued rivers set records for low water last month, including all-time records in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey reported Tuesday. The North Fork of the <LOCATION> Edisto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Orangeburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, averaged 141 million gallons of water per day for the month, the least amount of water for any month ever measured in that river in 49 years of recordkeeping. And on July 15 the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Muscoda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, recorded its lowest one-day flow ever at 1.2 billion gallons. That river has been measured for 75 years. Six other rivers, including the once mighty <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, had their lowest flows for any July on record, the survey reported. Even so, July had fewer record lows than the 33 recorded in June. `` Rains have brought some spotty improvement in streamflows and reservoir levels around the country,'' reported <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziglar </PERSON>, assistant secretary of interior. But, he added, `` the overall water-resources situation remains one of concern.'' `` Perhaps most striking, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> itself, pipeline for nearly half the streamflow in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, set a new monthly low, the lowest July in at least 54 years, and at least 13 percent lower than the record low set in June,'' <PERSON> Ziglar </PERSON> said. Flow in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, averaged 108 billion gallons per day during July, 60 percent below the median for the month. That flow broke the previous low record of 119 billion gallons per day set in July 1934. That also meant the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> remained the nation's second largest river in July, trailing the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION>, which averaged 159 billion gallons per day at <LOCATION> Massena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>. That was 11 percent below normal for the St. Lawrence Water flows for the remainder of the nation's Big Five rivers in July were 75.4 billion gallons per day in the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dalles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, 58 percent below normal; 28.7 billion gallons a day in the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Hermann </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, 41 percent below normal; and 19.8 billion in the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, 38 percent below normal. In addition to the record at <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> as measured at <LOCATION> Keokuk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, also set a record low for July at 10.6 billion gallons a day, 74 percent below normal. Besides the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Edisto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> rivers, records for low July streamflows were set on: _ The <LOCATION> Chippewa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Chippewa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, averaged 707 million gallons a day, 9 percent less than the record set in 1910 The flow was 65 percent below normal for the month. _ <LOCATION> Altahama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Doctortown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, was 74 percent below normal with a flow of 1.15 billion gallons per day, lowest in 56 years of records _ The <LOCATION> Apalachicola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Chattahoochee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION