<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Says Report of Baby Trafficking is False, Slanderous</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday rejected as false and slanderous a report that babies were sold to Americans for adoption and then dismembered, with their hearts and livers going to organ banks. `` There does not exist the slightest evidence ... that any adopted infant from any part of the world has been used in that way,'' the embassy said in a statement. The statement followed news reports that police raiding a house last week found seven infants _ presumably born of <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> mothers _ and several pregnant women who apparently intended to give their babies up for adoption. The infants, aged three months to six months, were taken to a hospital. Police detained three men and a woman. Judge <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> denounced the international `` trafficking'' of infants, and speculated that some might be dismembered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for their organs, which could be sold for hundreds of dollars. The embassy statement said a similar allegation was made in 1987 by <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>' secretary-general of Social Welfare, <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Villeda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>, who subsequently acknowledged he had no proof. The same allegation later cropped up in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, but that, too, was false, the statement said, alleging that communist newspapers were behind the rumor.
