<FIRST>r a AM-Eliana-AIDS     08-09 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eliana-AIDS,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>6-Year-Old With AIDS To Join Classmates, But Stay Behind Partition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ordered school officials to build a glass-front isolation booth inside a classroom so a 6-year-old who has AIDS can be taught with other children. The box, to measure at least 6 feet by 8 feet, is to have a desk and a potty chair, a sound system and a full-time teacher's aide. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> said in her ruling Monday she took into consideration the concerns of all involved in the case brought by the girl's adoptive mother, <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, against the <ORGANIZATION> Hillsborough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> last September. The judge expressed hope that once <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> is able to see how her mentally handicapped schoolmates cope, she will become toilet-trained and learn not to habitually place her thumb and forefinger in her mouth. Once that happens, the `` remote theoretical possibility'' that acquired immune deficiency syndrome could be spread to her classmates will be so slight that she must be allowed to sit in the classroom with her peers, the judge ruled. No AIDS cases have been proven to have been transmitted through exposure to urine, feces or saliva even though the virus that causes the disease has been found in these bodily secretions, the judge wrote. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON>'s lawyer, called the judge's ruling `` creative'' and said he hoped that within six weeks of starting school Aug. 29, <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> will have progressed enough to leave the booth. But a school official labeled the chamber idea `` sadistic,'' and compared it to child abuse. `` All I can do is see that little face in a bubble, very close to other children, but not able to take part in what the other children are doing,'' said <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Hillsborough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and a former teacher. `` I think I feel that this is as close to child abuse as it can be.'' <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosales </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Classroom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday that teachers who are aware of the ruling have had `` basically a positive attitude, although slightly apprehensive.'' Of the judge's decision, he said: `` I think she broke new ground, but it's still a middle-of-the road ruling.'' Ms. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> wanted her daughter schooled with other `` trainable mentally handicapped'' children at <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exceptional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, saying <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> needed the socialization and interaction. The school district wanted <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> taught at home out of fear she could transmit the AIDS virus. The girl has been in home instruction since June 1987. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Rampello </PERSON>, vice chairman of the school board, said, `` What the judge is asking us to do is unusual. But we're going to do it. I'm not criticizing; I'm not praising. We have to take all the good and all the problems that come with it, and all the consequences that come with it.'' <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> is one of 500 children in a pilot pediatric AIDS program who have been treated with experimental drugs including AZT. <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> said <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON>'s case of AIDS, probably contracted from transfusions of contaminated blood after her premature birth in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, is being held in check by the treatment. <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> presided over the case brought by the three <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> brothers in <LOCATION> Arcadia </LOCATION>, hemophiliacs who doctors believe were exposed to the virus through treatment with clotting agents from contaminated blood. She ordered the brothers admitted to regular classes last year, but after their house was burned, they moved with their family to another district.
