<FIRST>r i AM-Nagasaki     08-09 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nagasaki,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nagasaki Marks 43rd Anniversary Of Atom Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Church and temple bells tolled in <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> as thousands of people stopped in the streets Tuesday to remember the moment 43 years ago when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dropped an atomic bomb on the Japanese city. The city's mayor urged the government to clarify whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships are bringing nuclear weapons into <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. At 11:02 a.m., the moment when the bomb exploded in a burst of blinding light, bells tolled as many people on the streets and in shopping centers paused for a minute of silence. <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> became the target of the world's second atomic attack on Aug. 9, 1945. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dropped the first atomic bomb on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> three days earlier. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> surrendered about a week later to end World War II. At <LOCATION> Peace </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, near the point where the bomb exploded, about 20,000 people gathered for an annual service. Under a hot sun, people poured water over a memorial tablet to recall the cries of victims suffering from thirst and burns. Families presented a list of 2,295 names of bomb victims who died during the past year, bringing to 77,462 the number of post-war victims of nuclear radiation. Their names are inscribed on a vault near the park's peace statue. In the evening, about 2,000 Roman Catholics with candles walked through areas of the city once destroyed by the bombing, a church official said. Officials estimate up to 70,000 people died immediately from the explosion and the accompanying fire storms and radiation. About 70,000 residents still suffer from side effects of the plutonium bomb, doctors and social workers say. In the bombing of <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, an estimated 70,000 to 140,000 people died. About 350,000 people in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> hold certificates showing they were victims of the atomic bombings in the two cities. Since the war <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has followed a policy of `` three non-nuclear principles'': no possession, manufacture or introduction into the country of nuclear weapons. Speaking at the ceremony in <LOCATION> Peace </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Hitoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Motoshima </PERSON> criticized his government for allowing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships to dock in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> without verifying whether they carry nuclear weapons. `` The Japanese government should independently check whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships are carrying nuclear weapons when they call on Japanese ports, and make clear that it still is observing the three non-nuclear principles,'' <PERSON> Motoshima </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> bombing destroyed almost everything within a radius of more than half a mile, including 1,326 buildings and homes. It also demolished 23,500 homes and buildings outside that radius, according to a report by the city. The ancient port city of 450,000, has been rebuilt, with modern office towers and tree-lined avenues replacing the rubble-strewn landscape.
</TEXT>
