<HEAD>Amish Man Who Broke Sign Law Offered Community Service Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge has given an Amish man two weeks to perform five hours of community service or face a charge of criminal contempt for refusing to display a slow-moving-vehicle sign on his horse-drawn buggy. The charge could mean a $ 700 fine or up to 90 days in jail. <ORGANIZATION> Fillmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>'s ruling Monday postponed action on a contempt charge stemming from <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON>'s failure to pay a $ 20 fine. At an Aug. 29 hearing, <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said he would determine whether <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> performed the community service within the Amish community. `` There's no sense in getting into criminal contempt for non-payment of a $ 20 fine,'' the judge said. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> law requires non-motorized vehicles to display an orange sign outlined in red at night, and to carry it at all times. The Amish, who contend that displaying the bright signs is against their religion, are allowed to use a black triangle outlined in white on their buggies and wagons during the daytime. Last year, another judge ruled that <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> violated a state law for not having the proper sign on his horse-drawn buggy. The judge stayed imposition of a $ 20 fine on condition that <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> not violate that law during the next six months. But <PERSON> Hershberger </PERSON> was arrested a second time and ordered to pay the fine. He refused. Prosecutors in April charged him with criminal contempt of court, a misdemeanor. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said he modified the original sentence to permit community service because that option had been available in other cases involving Amish defendants.
