<FIRST>u w AM-TeenSurvey     08-09 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Survey,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Nation's Teens At Risk During Troubled Adolescent Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The teen-age years are troubled times when many young people drink too much, eat badly, are prone to injury and violence and often consider suicide, according to a survey released Tuesday. The data confirmed what many parents and counselors have long known or suspected _ the adolescent years can be dangerous. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, assistant health secretary and head of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, called the results `` somewhat dismaying.'' `` The results give us fresh insight concerning what our nation's teen-agers know and how they act concerning health and sex-related issues _ but they also show that too many young people, even when they know better, do n't always make the right health decisions,'' <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> said in a statement The survey, sponsored by health education groups and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, polled 11,000 eighth-graders and 10th-graders during the fall of 1987 from a nationally representative sample of 217 public and private schools. The margin of error was plus or minus 2 to 5 percentage points, depending on the frequency of the behavior reported, officials said. In one of the more startling findings, the study reported that 26 percent of the eighth-graders and 38 percent of the 10th-graders said they had had five or more drinks on one occasion during the two weeks preceding the survey. Also, 42 percent of the girls and 25 percent of the boys surveyed said they have `` seriously thought'' about committing suicide at some time in their lives. Nearly one in five girls and one in 10 boys of the total surveyed said they had actually tried to commit suicide. <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Popham </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> IOX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, which conducted the survey, said it was possible some teen-agers exaggerated their responses but that the results were still `` frightening'' even if the figures were off by half. `` I do n't think they are off,'' he said. `` I really think a lot of kids in their modest way say it's not worth it. There's a consistent pattern of hopelessness, of depression'' in some of the responses. In the area of health, the survey indicated that most teens understand that acquired immune deficiency syndrome or AIDS is transmitted by sexual intercourse and drug needles. They also know that condoms are effective in helping avoid AIDS and believe they should be used. But about half of the students were unsure or mistakenly believed that washing after sex reduces the chances of being infected. The teens displayed ignorance about other sexually transmitted diseases. The survey noted that 2.5 million teen-agers are infected with such diseases each year and that many teens can not identify common early signs of the infections. A majority of those surveyed do not know that taking birth control pills is ineffective in avoiding these diseases. More than a third said they would not know where to go for medical care if they caught a sexually transmitted disease. The survey showed that many teens do n't eat right even when they know they should. Nearly four of every 10 students said they eat fried foods four or more times a week. The average student ate three snacks a day that were high in fat or sugar, and 73 percent said they knew that eating such food may be related to heart problems or high blood pressure. Sixty-one percent of the girls and 28 percent of the boys said they had dieted during the past year, and about half of the students who dieted used unsafe methods such as fasting. Others tried diet pills, laxatives or vomiting. Unintentional injuries are the leading cause of death among people aged 15 to 25, with motor vehicle accidents accounting for more than 70 percent of accidental deaths. The survey showed that a substantial portion of teen-agers do not guard against such injuries. About 56 percent of those surveyed said they did not wear a seat belt the last time they rode in a vehicle. About 44 percent of 10th-graders and 32 percent of eighth-graders said they had ridden during the past month with a driver who had used drugs or alcohol. When they ride bicycles or motorcycles, according to the survey, 92 percent said they never wear a protective helmet. About half the boys and one-fourth of the girls reported having been involved in at least one fight during the year preceding the survey. Nearly one in five girls reported that during the past year while outside of school, someone tried to force them to have sex. About one-fourth of the boys said they have carried a knife to school at least once during the past year. Seven percent said they did so on a regular basis.
</TEXT>
