<HEAD>In Streets of Tehran, A Wary Mood</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s acting commander-in-chief, <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, said Tuesday his nation is seeking a comprehensive peace but must remain vigilant in the face of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> `` mischief.'' He reflected the relieved but wary mood on the streets of the war-weary capital. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> wo n't initiate any military actions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in light of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general setting Aug. 20 as the cease-fire date in the war. But he said that the soldiers should maintain their vigil against possible Iraqi attacks. `` The armed forces should not, from today, be the initiators of any kind of military and armed moves,'' said <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who also is speaker of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament, in a statement read over <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` But just like always, -LRB- <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> -RRB- will be ready to give an appropriate response to the mischiefs of the enemy.'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s message said that the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> `` has decided to create a lasting and comprehensive peace in the region and will continue its path,'' but that it is faced `` with enemies whose claims, promises and agreements can not be trusted.'' He said the Iraqis `` might resort to any agression and crime during the few days left until the cease-fire date and even after that.'' `` Islamic <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is proud before God for performing its holy duty of protecting justice, and the Iraqi Baathists should answer God and the people as to why they kindled the fire of war and what tney gained from it,'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> said. In the streets of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, Iranians greeted the announcement of the cease-fire date in the 8-year-old Iraq-Iran wa