<HEAD>Jurist Scolded In Klan Case Offers To Ban Himself From All
Government Cases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with 3 grafs to update with U.S. attorney's
filing Tuesday; picks up 4th graf pvs, `During the...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge who was chastised by a higher court for showing bias in favor of <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klansmen </PERSON> in a race violence case has offered to ban himself from litigation involving the federal government. But so far, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 60, has not drawn any public call for such blanket disqualification. <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>, appointed to the bench by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1982, scheduled a hearing on the issue for Friday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> on Tuesday filed a response on behalf of the government in which he said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` has at this time insufficient information to determine and no reason to believe that Judge <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>'s proposed general recusal is either necessary or appropriate.'' <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON>, who said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will not be represented at the hearing, said it is the government's view `` that the matter of recusal is better left for consideration on a case-by-case basis.'' <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>'s rulings against the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in the Klan litigation prompted the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> to remove him from the case in a bluntly worded order. `` During the course of this litigation,'' wrote 11th Circuit Judge <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, `` Judge <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>'s position has become hardened against the government, and he has evidenced a commitment that clearly reflects that he is no longer able to view these cases impartially.'' <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> had ruled that the actions of several Klansmen, accused of violating the civil rights of marchers in a violent confrontation at <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> in 1979, did not justify what <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> said were improper tactics used by the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poverty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, which <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> branded `` a counter-vigilante group.'' The center had sued the Klansmen, then gave their testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which used it to obtain indictments against them. <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> ruled the testimony inadmissible evidence and then did not follow 11th Circuit instructions to admit it as evidence. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Dees </PERSON>, director of the center, said his organization would take no position on <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>'s qualifications to preside over government cases. <PERSON> Dees </PERSON>, whose center over nearly two decades has handled a number of highly publicized civil rights and death penalty cases, said center attorneys will not attend Friday's hearing. `` We've never had any experience with Judge <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> in any other case,'' <PERSON> Dees </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomany </PERSON>, one of the attorneys for the Klansmen, said he plans to attend the hearing `` to submit any kind of briefs in support'' of the judge. `` I think he is a good and fair judge and he's ruled against our clients and against the government on occasion. More often than not, he's ruled against our clients. All in all, he's been impartial,'' said <PERSON> Gomany </PERSON>. `` This court is neither seeking praise nor condemnation,'' <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> wrote in June when he scheduled the hearing, `` but feels it is necessary that it create a forum for frank and serious discussion of a very serious subject, namely: ` Should a judge whose position is hardened against the government sit on the government's cases?''' <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>'s clerk said she was not aware of any briefs filed in advance of the hearing. The controversy began in 1979 in <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, when a march by the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> ended in a bloody confrontation with <PERSON> Klansmen </PERSON>, who beat police with clubs when officers tried to keep them away from the marchers. Shots were exchanged and several people were injured, none fatally. An initial <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation ended without indictments. But the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poverty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> filed a civil action against 50 <ORGANIZATION> Klansmen </ORGANIZATION>, seeking financial damages and bans on Klan actions. The center took testimony from <LOCATION> Klansmen </LOCATION>, then made it available to federal investigators, who used it to obtain indictments against nine Klansmen in 1984. <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>, however, blocked the testimony, saying it was inadmissible in the government's case. <PERSON> Acker </PERSON> said the Klan is `` a vigilante group which undoubtedly, from time to time, violates the constitutional rights of citizens.'' `` However, one vigilante group does not justify the creation and operation of -LRB- a -RRB- counter-vigilante group in violation of the constitutional rights of the first group.'' `` To tolerate a rape of the rights of the Klan would be a recognition that some sort of double standard exists for the application of constitutional protections,'' he said. The government appealed and the 11th Circuit ruled that the testimony should not be suppressed. The 11th Circuit ordered <PERSON> Acker </PERSON>'s removal from the case when the government filed a second appeal, arguing that he had failed to follow the circuit court's directions.
