<FIRST>r w AM-ArtificialInsemination     08-09 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Artificial Insemination,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Doctors Don't Test for AIDS Before Artificial Insemination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Only 44 percent of the nation's 11,000 physicians who perform artificial insemination test the donated semen for the AIDS virus, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> study released Tuesday. The study said that about 65,000 babies conceived by artificial insemination were born in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year. Semen for more than 30,000 of those babies was provided by anonymous sperm donors, the report by the congressional agency said. In a survey of 367 doctors who have at least four artificial insemination patients a year, only 44 percent, or about 161, said they test donors for evidence of the AIDS virus, the report said. Some doctors, however, reject semen if the donor is considered at risk of being infected with AIDS. Of the doctors surveyed, 16 percent said they rejected donors due to homosexual contacts; 13 percent for intravenous drug use; 12 percent for multiple heterosexual contacts; and 6 percent just for residency in an area where AIDS is common. Homosexuality, promiscuous sexual contact and IV drug use are all considered risk factors for contracting acquired immune deficiency syndrome. The study said 28 percent of the surveyed doctors tested sperm donors for syphilis; 27 percent for gonorrhea; 26 percent for hepatitis; 23 percent for chlamydia; and 6 percent for herpes. Fifteen surveyed sperm banks, which collect and store semen for use under the direction of doctors, said they screen donor semen for AIDS, although one sperm bank said the test was performed `` only if the donor were considered to be from a high risk group.'' There have been no confirmed reports of women infected with AIDS from donated semen, but in two locations semen from men later found to have AIDS has been used for artificial insemination, the report said. In <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austrialia </LOCATION>, the study says, there have been several women who were exposed to AIDS from insemination of infected semen. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> recommended last February that all donated semen be frozen and quarantined for at least six months. This would enable the semen donors to be tested for AIDS, a disease that may not show up in blood tests for months after the sperm is infective. The <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study, however, showed that 22 percent of the surveyed physicians used only fresh semen, usually from the husband or partner of the woman. Of the frozen semen used, 75 percent had a quarantine period, generally of three months, the report said. In general, the report said, commercial sperm banks were more likely to screen donors effectively for infertility, AIDS and genetic defects than were individual physicians. About 20 percent of the women requesting artificial insemination are turned down by the physicians, the study said. Over half the doctors said they reject unmarried women or those whom they consider psychologically immature. Almost all of the doctors said they were willing to match the woman's specifications for donor's race, eye color and body type, and a majority also would match specifications for educational attainment, intelligence quotient and religion. Artificial insemination is a procedure whereby sperm is inserted into the vagina or uterus by syringe or other artificial means. The technique is commonly used for women whose husbands are sterile or whose husbands' semen requires processing to enhance the chances of conception. Unmarried women also request artificial insemination, the report said. AIDS is caused by a virus that can be transmitted through blood products or sperm. AIDS kills by attacking the victims' immune system, making them susceptible to disease and some types of cancer. There have been no known cases of full recovery from AIDS infection.
</TEXT>
