<HEAD>U.S. Officials, Back From Moscow, See No Sign Of Soviet Military
Reduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials saw no signs during last week's trip to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> of a reduction in Soviet military forces or spending, despite Soviet assurances of a new defense policy, an American official said Monday. The official, who accompanied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> on the trip but who spoke on condition of anonymity, said, `` It does not seem to us evident yet that there is any change in force structure or resources that the Soviets are committing to their military effort.'' The official was in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> to brief the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s four days of talks with Soviet Defense Minister <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> and unprecedented tours of secret Soviet military bases. The council, the highest decision-making body of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, is made up of representatives of the 16 countries in the alliance. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official told reporters the Americans discussed the Soviets' so-called defensive doctrine, under which emphasis would be placed on defending territory rather than seizing or holding it. `` When we look at their forces,'' he said, `` the things that bother us for example is their heavy emphasis'' on tanks, artillery, engineer bridging units and airborne forces. He said these are the type of troops that would be used to grab territory. `` Now,'' he said, `` the Soviets say they are changing to a defensive doctrine and they do n't have that objective. ... We made clear to them that we must pay attention specifically to what their capabilities are.'' `` We would welcome seeing changes ... away from those kinds of forces that would help us relieve our concerns about the offensive capabilities of the Soviet army,'' he said. He did say, however, that Soviet officials provided some evidence that military exercises `` seem to be shifting ... to reflect'' the new doctrine. `` We do n't dismiss the utility of that or changes of that kind on the Soviet side,'' he said. Soviet authorities also told their <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> counterparts they were putting together a better accounting of their defense spending, the official said. `` We do n't have anything concrete as to whether or not they are in fact applying less resources to the military or not right now,'' he said. `` We do n't see evidence of that in terms of what you can see in their own production output and other efforts.'' He said Soviet officials did not dispute <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> estimates that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> spends 15 percent to 17 percent of its economic output on the military. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense spending amounts to about 6 percent of the gross national product, the total value of goods and services produced by the economy. The official said the two delegations also discussed ways to prevent accidental shootings or other serious incidents between the two countries' forces during peacetime. In 1985, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military observer was shot and killed in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> while making what <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> authorities said was a proper tour of the area. The first meeting of a working group on preventing such incidents was scheduled to meet in the fall, the official said. No date or place has yet been set. This was the third meeting between <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>. They met last March in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and again at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit in June. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was not expecting dramatic changes in its military ties with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` It would be, I think, unfounded to anticipate a sea change in our relationships with them in the military area,'' he said. `` These discussions in and of themselves, do not change the security situation that we have to face. ... We find no grounds in these contacts we have had for unilaterally altering our military structure or our defense posture or the need for readiness or defense spending.''
