ge dumping is a throwaway approach to our waste problem and contributes to the overall ocean pollution problem.'' Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, agreed. `` We're treating the oceans as a cesspool,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> first ordered an end to the ocean dumping of sewage sludge in 1972. Five years laters, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> directed that the dumping be ended by 1981. But the nine municipalities in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> successfully sued in federal court to ignore that deadline. `` We need a firm deadline, in the law, to ban the ocean dumping of sewage sludge,'' said <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>. `` Only then will alternatives be put in place. Only then will the dumping stop.''
