<HEAD>State Department Sends Investigators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> specialists will help investigate the bombing of the motorcade carrying Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. A leftist guerrilla group calling itself the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bolivar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commando </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility for the Monday explosion, which investigators said they believed was intended to frighten rather than kill. Three cars were damaged but no one was injured. <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> said drug traffickers probably were behind the attack. `` In terms of the way it was done, and the amount of explosives that were used, it ... probably came from narcotics dealers who are protesting the vigorous legislation and action the <LOCATION> Bolivian </LOCATION> government is taking,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> told reporters during a visit to <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. He said the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> had no specific warnings of an attack on <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, but `` there was a lot of security down there.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION> on Tuesday, with a stop in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, to meet with former President <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Banzer </PERSON>. Police said the bomb consisted of several sticks of dynamite buried by the roadside and connected to a detonator by more than 40 yards of cable. The explosion hurled rocks and chunks of pavement at cars in the motorcade, only four of which were armored. One of those damaged was the armored car carrying <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Helena </PERSON>. Callers to local news agencies, purporting to speak for the <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolivar </PERSON> <PERSON> Commando </PERSON>, described the group as `` anti-imperialist and indigenous.'' They also claimed responsibility in its name for a bombing earlier this year at the home of the La Paz jail warden and an explosion during a visit by King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in April 1987. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Bolivian investigators said they had information on the group and believe it is responsible for bank robberies and bombings. Other anonymous callers claimed responsibility on behalf of a group called the <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarate </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilca </PERSON>, but police discounted the claim. <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> has had few instances of political violence in recent years. The few bombings reported generally have caused no injuries. Labor and left-wing political groups had condemned the <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> visit as interference in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s internal affairs. Farmers and labor have criticized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid in fighting the drug trade and reducing the coca leaf crop because it threatens the livelihoods of nearly 350,000 farmers who grow coca, the raw material for cocaine. A Bolivian law that took effect two weeks ago would phase out production on 90 percent of coca plantations and impose stiff penalties on cocaine producers and traffickers. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has 40 military trainers, drug enforcement and border patrol agents working with <LOCATION> Bolivian </LOCATION> police in the anti-drug campaign.
