<FIRST>u w AM-DroughtRelief     08-09 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Relief,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves $3.9 Billion Drought Relief Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved a $ 3.9 billion aid package for drought-stricken farmers Tuesday and sent the measure to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who made known he intends to sign it. `` We have kept the faith,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the bill, 383-18. `` To all who will be helped by this legislation, our promise has been kept.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> devoted only brief debate to the measure, which emerged from a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> last week and won <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> raced to put the legislation on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk before it begins a three-week break Friday. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters hours earlier there was no doubt that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will sign the measure. Provisions call for government payments to farmers who have lost more than 35 percent of their crops because of drought, hail, excessive moisture or related damage, such as that caused by insects. The payments would be equal to 65 percent of their losses over the 35 percent threshhold level. Additional payments would be available for the farmers hardest hit by the blazing sun and lack of rainfall that have darkened fields in the midcontinent. Farmers who have received government income-support payments in advance would not have to repay them in many cases under the legislation. Those receiving payments would be required to purchase federal crop insurance for their 1989 crops. The measure would make feed assistance available for producers of many varieties of livestock, including cattle, sheep, goats, pigs, poultry, horses used for food or in food production and fish used for food. Bills involving major farm subsidies have come in for substantial criticism on fiscal grounds from urban lawmakers in recent years. But the drought measure escaped such complaints for the most part. Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, R-Pa., did complain about a $ 5.5 million authorization contained in the measure for a temperature control system on the <LOCATION> Sacremento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Shasta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dam </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to aid salmon spawning `` So the bill is going to take care of yuppies, too, and make sure their salmon mousse supply is not interfered with?'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. He grumbled that the public is `` sick and tired of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> using every sort of emergency to pork barrel.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> replied that the drought could be even worse in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> next year than it is now. The legislation is a bipartisan product that was produced in record time _ about six weeks _ with lawmakers hurrying to finish their work and win the president's approval before any second thoughts about the expense set in or the bill accumulated so many special-interest provisions that it would be impossible to pass. `` This bill is the product of a tremendous concerted effort to produce relief for drought-stricken farmers,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., the ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Lawmakers and the administration believe the measure can be paid for with funds that the government will save because of the drought. Income-support payments, known to farmers as deficiency payments, increase in proportion to the size of the producer's crop yield. The drought has reduced these yields and thus slashed the amount that the government will be required to spend. By some estimates, the savings could be as much as $ 7 billion. Farmers whose yields are reduced by more than 75 percent will come in for increased government payments under the legislation. These payments will be equal to 90 percent of losses over that 75 percent level.
</TEXT>
