<HEAD>Summary of Gulf News</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A cease-fire is scheduled to begin Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war, which has killed or wounded more than 1 million people. Here, at a glance, are developments Tuesday in the efforts to end the war:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UNITED NATIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The financially strapped <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> created a $ 74 million observer corps to monitor the truce between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, but Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said, `` I simply do not have the money'' to pay for it. <PERSON> Marrack </PERSON> <PERSON> Goulding </PERSON>, undersecretary-general in charge of peacekeeping operations, said the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> probably would be summoned to special session this week to assess the membership for funds. Twenty-five countries will provide 350 unarmed observers. The five permanent <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ will not provide personnel because the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> wants to avoid involvement by the major powers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAQ</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, state television announced Monday's cease-fire declaration after midnight, declaring victory in the war and three days of celebration. Fireworks exploded over the <LOCATION> Tigris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and tens of thousands of rounds of ammunition were fired into the air.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Iranians greeted the announcement of the cease-fire date with a sense of relief mixed with skepticism that it will mean lasting peace. In <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s acting commander-in-chief, <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, said his nation is seeking peace but must remain vigilant in the face of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> `` mischief.'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> wo n't initiate any military actions, but soldiers should maintain their vigil against possible attacks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S.-GULF</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the administration welcomed the cease-fire announcement and would bear `` its fair share of the cost'' of the observer force, including transportation and equipment. `` It has been a major aim of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to bring this war to an end,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` We now look forward to the implementation ... in all its parts'' of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for a cease-fire.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CARLUCCI</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will withdraw most of its naval forces from the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> only when it is convinced that the cease-fire has taken effect. `` We have no desire to keep our ships, our people, there any longer than necessary. At the same time, we do n't want to put them in any danger,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NAVY-GULF</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Chief Pentagon spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> had completed its 54th convoy operation of the year with the guided-missile frigate <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> escorting the reflagged <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> tanker <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> up the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had not received reports of fighting Tuesday between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, but added: `` I do not have a definitive report that all hostilities have ceased. I ca n't speak to that one way or another.''
