<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> confessed Tuesday he helped hijack a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jetliner to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in 1985, but said he is `` not ready to do something like that again'' and denied he killed the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver aboard. In a statement read in court, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said the four hijackers were trying to force the release of Lebanese Shiite Moslems imprisoned in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Shortly after the ordeal was over, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> released approximately 700 Shiites. `` The decision to hijack the plane came after everything else failed,'' <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said in his surprise confession. `` There was no other way to free the prisoners other than the means chosen.'' Thirty-nine Americans were held captive for 17 days and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was killed. His body was thrown onto a <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> airport runway. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> is being tried on charges of air piracy and murder in the June 1985 <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> hijacking. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government also has indicted <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> on charges of air piracy and murder. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> denounced <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for `` illegal conduct'' in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, condemned the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and said another hijacker had killed <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>. One of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s lawyers said <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> felt sorry for `` everyone who suffered harm.'' In reflecting on the hijacking, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> told the court: `` I am not ready to do something like that again.'' `` As I took part in the action, that happened out of the belief that there was