<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 South African soldiers prepared Tuesday to withdraw from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> as part of a peace accord, but their rebel allies threatened to fight until they are included in peace talks. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will begin a three-week pullout of its troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> on Wednesday under terms of a cease-fire reached with <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The accord also sets a Nov. 1 starting date for a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan to bring independence to <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. An estimated 3,000 South African soldiers are in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has an estimated 50,000 soldiers in the country. In <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, which has close ties to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, the national news agency said <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> were being pulled back to positions north of the 16th parallel, roughly 90 miles north of the Namibian border, as part of the agreement. The accord, announced Monday, was reached in five rounds of U.S.-mediated peace talks among <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The region's two main guerrilla armies were excluded. Spokesmen for the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which has fought for Namibian independence since 1966, said it would join in a truce in the territory starting Sept. 1. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is believed to have a strong chance of taking power in free elections envisioned under the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> independence plan. But the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGA