<HEAD>Status of Five Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola, AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Some international conflicts this week appear headed toward resolution. Others hold the promise of settlement, but negotiations are stalled. Here, at a a glance, is the status of some major wars around the world:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAN-IRAQ</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A cease-fire takes effect Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf War, which has killed or wounded more than 1 million people. The cease-fire will be monitored by a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> observer force.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANGOLA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will begin pulling its troops out of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> on Wednesday, Aug. 10. The pro-Western <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas, who with South African help have fought the Cuban-supported Marxist government of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, say they will continue their war until Angolan leaders agree to negotiate a power-sharing arrangement. In neighboring <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> plan to grant independence to the South African-ruled territory has a starting date of Nov. 1. The Angolan-supported <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas, fighting since 1966 for Namibian independence, say they will join in a truce Sept. 1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AFGHANISTAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Half the estimated 120,000 Soviet troops backing <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s Marxist government against anti-communist rebels are to be out of that country by next Monday, under accords signed in April The Soviets are to withdraw all their military units by next Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAMBODIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Communist <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, whose troops prop up a <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> government against Marxist and non-Marxist resistance groups, said last month it would pull its forces out by early 1990. But no significant progress was reported in subsequent peace negotiations, between representatives of the Vietnamese and <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> governments on one side, and <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance leaders on the other.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Peace talks between the leftist Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, have been suspended since the last session broke up in disagreement June 9. The Sandinistas have arrested opposition leaders, shut down opposition media outlets and expelled some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats. The Contras have elected new hard-line political leaders and have been accused of carrying out attacks in the countryside in violation of an informal cease-fire. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has yet to reach agreement on resumption of suspended aid to the Contras.
</TEXT>
