<HEAD>Iraq Celebrates, Declares Victory in Gulf War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt
^Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to include more celebrations Tuesday night
and early Wednesday; PICKS up 5th pvs `A woman'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> declared victory Tuesday in the war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the sky over the <LOCATION> Tigris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> blazed with fireworks. When the announcement of a cease-fire was read over state television soon after midnight Monday, exuberant Iraqis fired tens of thousands of rounds of ammunition into the sky. The television urged Iraqis to `` celebrate the great victory achieved by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'' on `` the greatest day of all.'' It declared three days of celebration to mark the end of the 8-year-old war, which killed or wounded more than 1 million people and cost the combatants hundreds of billions of dollars. It also appealed for a halt to the shooting, which caused an undisclosed number of casualties, but to no avail. Gunfire continued 24 hours later. `` This is the pressure of pent-up emotion which has built for eight years,'' Iraqi writer <PERSON> Jabra </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jabra </PERSON> told a visitor as shots sounded in the streets outside his home Tuesday night. Streets throughout the capital were gridlocked with horn-honking cars into the early hours Wednesday as Iraqis jumped from their vehicles to dance in the streets, or dangled from windows or car rooftops. After the announcement on television, a man at the entrance of the Rashid hotel shouted `` The war is over! Victory for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>!'' and gazed at the flashes overhead. A woman beside him said: `` The war is over, praise be to God!'' Tracers, flares and machine-gun bullets streamed into the air for hours after the announcement. The crack and stutter of firing filled the night. `` Here, take this!'' joyful security men told a reporter, thrusting a loaded <PERSON> Kalashnikov </PERSON> assault rifle at him. The guards later fired the gun into the air, laughing with other security men across the street who also were shooting. A car in the hotel parking lot had a new bullet hole in its hood. Children scampered about collecting empty cartridge casings. Celebrants danced on the beds of pickups and waved palm fronds from car windows. People beat drums and sang as others danced in the streets. Later Tuesday, a day after <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> announced that a cease-fire would begin Aug. 20, the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Baath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> organized processions in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. Marchers waved pictures of President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>. They raised <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> flags beside banners reading `` The Hero of Peace, President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'' and `` Masses of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> Congratulate the Hero of Victory.'' In what the official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> called the `` Communique of Communiques,'' the president proclaimed the three-day holiday and said: `` In the name of all Arabs and mankind, we call on Iraqis to celebrate this great victory.'' For the first time in nearly eight years, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> did not issue a daily war communique. The last one, No. 3288 on Monday, reported only minor skirmishes. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> attended a morning celebration at Grand Festivities Park in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. The news agency said <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> al </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, emir of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, telephoned congratulations and declared Thursday a day of celebration in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The official news agency said soldiers fired 10,000 artillery rounds to celebrate. It said 101 shots were fired in joy during each of the five Moslem prayer times Tuesday in 17 Iraqi cities and governorates. Moslem are required to face <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, birthplace of the prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, and pray each day at dawn, noon, afternoon, evening and night.
