<HEAD>Defense Minister Outlines Problems in Soviet Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Minister <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> says the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> must fight complacency in the ranks and delays in new weapons programs if it is to keep other countries from gaining military superiority. In an article published Tuesday, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> recommended ambitious action to cleanse the military of outdated attitudes, improve the reliability of military hardware and make the `` human factor'' dominant in the Soviet military. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>'s article in the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> was an unusually frank account of problems in the Soviet military. Before <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> began his policy of glasnost, or openness, the military was presented only as strong and problem-free. The defense minister has spoken candidly of the military's problems since he was appointed in May 1987 The 64-year-old army genera was quoted as saying in a speech three months ago that Soviet soldiers in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> lack discipline and battle readiness. His latest comments encompassed the entire Soviet armed forces. `` Our military thought is still partially constrained by inertia, routine and a lack of competition of ideas and opinions,'' he wrote. He said the gap must be reduced between theoretical research on new weapons and their actual development and deployment, and oversimplification and showiness must be removed from military training. Bureaucracy and a tendency to blame problems on others plagues the Soviet armed forces at all levels, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> declared. He said young commanders, soldiers and officers take a passive attitude toward deficiences. Senior officers must not alienate themselves from those they command, he wrote, and `` all ideological and political upbringing must be built so that the person is always in the center of attention.'' <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> said the goal should not be `` accumulation of military might of the armed forces ... but maintenance of the might at a level that precludes military superiority over us and guarantees a reliable defense.'' Last week, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> toured Soviet military facilities with <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, the visiting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense secretary.
