<HEAD>Flamenco Prodigy Mixes Music With Homework</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSE TINSLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maya </PERSON> ca n't accept all the offers he receives to play his guitar in flamenco concerts because there are times when he has to stay home to do his homework. At 10, the guitar prodigy is already a veteran of three years of flamenco shows, and his audiences have included <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> and Queen <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION>. Last August he was invited to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> by King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> and <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Noor </PERSON> to play at a royal wedding in <LOCATION> Aqaba </LOCATION>. `` It's always nice to play for kings and queens,'' the youngster said during in a recent interview. `` They're nice people to meet.'' Following a recent sold-out performance in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, a music critic for <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s leading daily, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pais </LOCATION>, called <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON> exceptionally talented. <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON> began playing professionally three years ago when his guitar was nearly as big as he was. He has been studying since he was 5 with his father, the noted flamenco guitarist <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Maya </PERSON>. He also studies classical guitar at a <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> conservatory. <PERSON> Maya </PERSON> says his son's talent and success are rooted in hard work, not in any type of gift from God. Flamenco, which encompasses singing, guitar-playing, dancing and hand-clapping, traces its roots to 16th century southern <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> where it emerged as the artistic response of Gypsies to widespread repression, and was influenced by elements of Jewish and Moorish music. Sometimes, his father lets <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON> stay up to play in a 3 a.m. `` juerga'' _ a sort of flamenco jam session _ at <LOCATION> Candela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s hangout for flamenco artists and aficionados where he wows the late-night crowd with the depth and sensitivity of his playing Professional flamenco guitarists call him a young maestro who plays at a level far advanced for his age. World-famous guitarist <PERSON> Sabicas </PERSON> says he has never heard a youngster play so well. <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON> has already appeared twice in the annual `` Flamenco Summit'' in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, on a youth program in 1985 and as a featured soloist last year, a spot usually reserved for such talents as <PERSON> Paco </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucia </PERSON>. <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Maya </PERSON> says <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON>, his other son and two daughters often get together with him at home and hold their own `` juergas.'' `` As Gypsies, we externalize our feelings and emotions,'' the father said. `` We could be sitting around, and then we start singing and dancing just because we feel like it.'' <PERSON> Maya </PERSON> says his son has been fortunate not to encounter the discrimination many Gypsy children suffer in Spanish schools. `` He's very down to earth, and in the school, people look up to him,'' he said. <PERSON> Jeronimo </PERSON>, who wants to travel to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ `` to see the big <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> skyscrapers'' _ also likes Brazilian and jazz guitar and says his favorite classical composers include <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> and <PERSON> Debussy </PERSON>, the latter particularly because many of his compositions were based on flamenco patterns.
</TEXT>
