<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Joy'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Elektra </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> `` Joy'' is a steamy set of soul songs that never overheats, due to the restraint of the tempos, arrangements and <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON>' delivery Even when <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> sings of `` explosions of ecstacy flowing from you and me'' -LRB- on `` 2 a.m.'' -RRB-, his cooing manner is such that the words would probably slip right past <PERSON> Tipper </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. The song titles _ `` Can We Be Lovers,'' `` I'm Ready,'' `` Love Is the Power'' _ show that <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> is obsessed with the same thing as <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> is less overt. The accompaniment steers clear of lead guitars or horns that would clash with <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON>' smooth style. Drums, bass and low-profile keyboards dominate. The closest thing to a frill is three female backup singers; <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> plays off them when he raps -LRB- briefly enough to avoid being corny -RRB- and when he improvises nicely on the chorus of `` Through the Falling Rain.'' The eight love songs on `` Joy'' are all played at mid-tempo. <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON>' message is clear: this is music for romancing, not dancing. _ By <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'' -LRB- Sire -RRB- _ <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> The story's so irresistible, you almost want to will it to be true. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, Rock' n' Roll Hall of Fame member and erstwhile <PERSON> Beach </PERSON> <PERSON> Boy </PERSON>, releases his first solo LP after 20 years of being nearly incapacitated by mental illness. Can the lost genius ever be found? Not really. In one respect, this new album is a triumph. Few people honestly expected <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> to ever again release listenable music of any form, so anything more is gravy. But let's be honest. Despite some pleasant moments, `` <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'' ca n't compare with any of the early'60s Beach Boys classics, nor a lot of other good music happening today. It's a nondescript album that floats by without any songs grabbing hold and shaking out any reaction. Frankly, both the Smithereens and XTC alter-egos <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Stratosphear </LOCATION> have written better <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> tributes in the past year than <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> himself. Back when he was young, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s classic `` In My Room'' spoke universally to teen-agers who occasionally need to escape into themselves and not feel childish about it. But a generation has passed, and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> still has n't left his room. In `` Love and Mercy,'' he talks of `` lyin' in my room'' and seeing `` a lot of people out there hurtin' and it really scares me.'' The prescription, love and mercy, is n't much different from what the <ORGANIZATION> Beatles </ORGANIZATION> suggested 21 years ago. `` Baby Let Your Hair Grow Long'' suggests a troubled girl may cure her problems with an adjustment in grooming. A naivete that seemed charming 25 years ago is less so now. And, musically, what once seemed effortless is now labored. Too many rhythms are ponderous and the <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Spector </PERSON> touches in the production mostly sound dated. There are some high points: `` Walkin' the Line,'' with the vocal help of <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Trent </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Arby </PERSON>, is breezy and warm, and `` Meet Me in My Dreams Tonight'' is a pretty fantasy song. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s old Beach Boy mates do n't appear, but the a capella `` One for the Boys'' is a worthy tribute. And the eight-minute concept song, `` <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>,'' is not the disaster that its length and lyrics suggest. No, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> does n't embarrass himself with this effort. But do n't throw away your old Beach Boy albums. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
