<HEAD>Venezuela Seeking New Foreign Loans Amid Growing Debt Frustration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government mission charged with extracting new loans from foreign commercial banks begins its difficult task this week amid <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s growing frustration at its inability to escape from its vicious circle of foreign debt. The team, headed by Finance Minister <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>, will try to convince banks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> to lend up to $ 3 billion to cover this year's estimated $ 2.5 billion balance of payments deficit. The discussions could be rocky: as <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> blames its inability to grow out of its economic problems on the weight of the foreign debt, while foreign banks see its problem as one of lax domestic policy. `` We understand that the debt is the Gordian knot of our current -LRB- economic -RRB- situation and we have decided to cut it,'' President <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> stated emphatically in a televised address last week. The balance of payments deficit is the product of continued low oil prices, which could limit income from <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s main export to just $ 8.2 billion this year. Scheduled payments on its $ 34 billion foreign debt, estimated at $ 5 billion this year, will absorb 60 percent of that, severely limiting the nation's prospects for growth in an election year. But the government is equally frustrated by the fact that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> paid over $ 30 billion in capital and interest between 1983, when its debt problems began, and last year, but its total debt has remained virtually unchanged. Venezuelan officials claim commercial bank creditors have reneged on a promise to provide <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> with new funds and help it regain access to international financial markets. The nation's $ 20.34 billion foreign debt refinancing agreement, first signed in 1986, was revised early in 1987 to allow for more favorable terms _ including a clause in which banks promised to `` look favorably'' upon requests for new loans. But besides an estimated $ 3.5 billion in short-term lines of credit and a $ 100 million issue of Republic of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> bonds, no new balance of payments loans have been made. `` Servicing the foreign debt -LRB- was -RRB- made under the promise that financial flows would be renewed ... -LRB- debt service -RRB- has been an obligation that has limited our possibilities to eradicate our crisis,'' <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> said. The frustration has led to persistent rumors in recent weeks that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> might declare a unilateral debt payment moratorium, as some government party members want. But <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> and other top administration officials said any suspension of payments would occur only if this week's mission fails, and even then, only in concert with commercial banks. And <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> said before leaving for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> last weekend that any new talks to seek more favorable terms on the refinanced debt would begin only after a new administration takes office early next year. `` A temporary suspension of payments -LRB- this year -RRB- is a far-off possibility, but it is a possibility,'' said <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON>, a private economist who advises the government on economic policy. But government efforts to control the domestic impact of the debt are showing signs of strain. Due to lack of sufficient income, government spending programs designed to promote growth have been based on internal debt, which has risen to 7 percent of gross domestic product, according to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. The spending resulted in domestic growth of 5 percent in 1986, for the first time in eight years. But growth slowed to 3 percent last year and, according to private estimates, could be flat again this year. Inflation, which the government hoped to limit to 15 percent this year, already had topped 12 percent through July, and private economists estimate it could reach 25 percent by December. And the free market exchange rate for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, an important indicator of local business psychology, zoomed last week to more than 38 bolivars, a record level and nearly three times the official exchange rate. Nevertheless, analysts feel the government has room to adopt policies which would help solve the domestic imbalances, including raising domestic interest rates and increasing fiscal revenues from public services. The financial mission is armed with an outline of possible steps the government could take in return for new cash. Foreign bankers say they probably would require such measures _ which would be similar to austerity guidelines often recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> _ as a condition of any new loans. Foreign bankers also say <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> should look for new money in other places first, which usually means the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>. But <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> is unlikely to want to change its policy of avoiding an <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> connection in order to maintain the freedom to set its own economic priorities. `` Politically, for a government ending its term and in an electoral year, -LRB- going to the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- would be very, very difficult,'' said <PERSON> Maza </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
