<SECOND>PM-CBS-TV Station, Bjt,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Agrees To Buy Independent TV Station in Miami</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, flush with cash from sale of major non-broadcasting assets, says it plans to look for more prospects in the wake of its agreement to purchase an independent television station in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> for $ 59 million. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that its agreement to acquire WCIX-TV from <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, also calls for it to assume certain program obligations, which a CBS spokesman said were valued at about $ 13 million. <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> president, in announcing the deal said `` we are continuing to evaluate other potential properties with an eye toward further acquisitions.'' Financial analysts said the deal seemed good for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON>, who had been faulted for failing to buy more stations with the $ 3 billion amassed by selling assets such as its records and magazine businesses. On Wall Street, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> stock slipped 12 -LCB- cents a share to $ 162.87 -LCB- on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The purchase of the station, which is subject to regulatory approval, would allow <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> to maintain its presence in the fast-growing <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> television market at only a fraction of the price a network affiliate likely would have commanded. <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> is the nation's 16th largest TV market. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> was outbid last year in an effort to buy its <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> affiliate, <ORGANIZATION> WTVJ </ORGANIZATION>, by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which offered $ 270 million. <ORGANIZATION> WTVJ </ORGANIZATION> still carries CBS programs under an affiliation agreement that ends in January, when it is expected to become an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> affiliate. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Appert </PERSON>, a media analyst for the investment firm C.J. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grenfell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> WCIX </ORGANIZATION> purchase `` looks like an excellent deal.'' `` They bought a new network affiliate station for an incredibly low price,'' he said. <PERSON> Appert </PERSON> said independent stations command lower prices because they have higher programming costs, attract smaller audiences and generate lower advertising revenue. Affiliates get some programming from the network and often can charge higher ad rates for programs such as local news that may appear just before network programs, he said. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, media analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said buying an independent station `` might send a dangerous signal'' to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> affiliates who have a competing independent station in their market. `` There might be a risk in any market where there is a VHF independent,'' he said. A VHF station is one operating on Channels 2 through 13. But <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, vice president and general manager of <ORGANIZATION> KCTV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and a former head of the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> affiliates board, said there were only a handful of markets where that situation existed. `` It sounds to me like it's a smart buy,'' he said. Affiliates had been urging <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> to buy a few stations to demonstrate his commitment to the network. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> told them he wanted to do so, but that the asking prices were too high. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> owns television stations in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> that reach 19.4 percent of the country's viewers. With <ORGANIZATION> WCIX </ORGANIZATION>, its stations would reach 20.8 percent of the country. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s parent has seven stations reaching 22.4 percent of the country; <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has eight stations reaching 24.4 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regulations limit network companies to owning a maximum of 12 stations reaching 25 percent of the country. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> also announced Monday that <ORGANIZATION> WPEC-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, would become a CBS affiliate in January. The station is now an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> affiliate, and the signing is seen as helping <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> reach an audience north of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> where the <ORGANIZATION> WCIX </ORGANIZATION> signal is weak.
