<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar edged down slightly against the Japanese yen today, while share prices dropped for the third straight day on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. After opening at 133.62 yen, down from Monday's close of 133.97 yen, the dollar remained in a narrow range between 133.52 and 133.73 yen in slow trading. It closed at 133.58 yen, down 0.39 yen from Monday's close. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 109.06-point loser Monday, lost 82.76 points, or 0.29 percent, to close at 28,170.36. Volume traded on the first section of the exchange was a light 650 million shares. The volume has plunged drastically since Monday when it declined to 650 million shares, the first time the daily volume traded fell below 1 billion shares since July 25. Dealers said investors were not active in the market because <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is entering a major holiday season. `` As seen in the low volume, the market is not moving energetically and only limited shares are being traded,'' said a dealer at a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` This situation will likely continue until mid-August. `` Most foreign fund managers seem to be out of town for vacation and there are not many people left in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> who can move a large amount of funds,'' the dealer added.
