<HEAD>Richard Kahn Elected President of Motion Picture Academy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Marketing executive <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> has been elected as the 26th president of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, sponsors of the Academy Awards. <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, the first member of the public relations branch of the academy to be elected president, succeeds director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>. Elected last week as vice presidents of the academy were writer <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Corwin </PERSON>, public relations executive <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehme </PERSON>. Cinematographer <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Westheimer </PERSON> was reelected as treasurer, and editor <PERSON> Donn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cambern </PERSON> was named secretary. The academy also elected 13 governors to its 36-member board, including director <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jewison </PERSON> and producer <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaentz </PERSON>.
