<SECOND>PM-Love Canal,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Love Canal's Next 10 Years Will Be As Important As Its First
Decade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years after Love Canal was declared a national disaster area because buried chemicals were oozing to the surface, the largely abandoned neighborhood remains at the center of environmental debate. The former chemical dump that forced hundreds of families from their homes has been fenced off and surrounded with clay and plastic liners to prevent chemicals from leaking into groundwater. Corroding drums of chemicals have been separated and complex runoff monitoring and collection systems have been built. But even though the contamination has been largely contained and state officials have begun to talk about restoring the neighborhood to residential use, critics think Love Canal and hundreds of similar sites throughout the nation will remain potential disasters until a safe disposal method is found. `` We've spent the first 10 years catching up on the sins of the past,'' acknowledged <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, who noted that the discovery of Love Canal's threat was largely responsible for federal toxic waste cleanup legislation. `` The future will have to be spent changing industrial processes and people's attitudes about waste generation,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. `` In many ways the next 10 years will be more important than the first.'' Love Canal, an abandoned waterway project, was used by the <ORGANIZATION> Hooker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to dispose of thousands of pounds of chemical wastes in the 1940s. <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON> made herbicides and pesticides. In the 1950s, the canal and its contents were covered and homes and an elementary school were built. It was n't until the early 1970s that people began to notice foul smells in their basements and oily puddles in their yards. They also began to notice higher-than-usual incidences of miscarriages, birth defects, cancer, leukemia, neurological disease, allergies, epilepsy and suicides. But government was slow to react. It took mass protests and town meetings turned into near riots to prod the state into action. On Aug. 7, 1978, President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> declared a state of emergency at Love Canal. Eventually, 728 homes in a 50-block area were evacuated and the elementary school and 228 of the houses were torn down. The state and federal governments filed multimillion-dollar lawsuits against <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON>. The cases are still being pursued against the company's parent, <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Today, inside the fenced dump, crews in protective suits carry out small projects to shore up containment walls or check monitoring wells Outside the fence, houses are boarded up and decaying. A few are still inhabited. `` We always hoped they'd decide that it was safe to live here and that things would return to normal one day,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, a retiree who stayed in his house two blocks from the dump site. Some 175 other families are awaiting the results of a state habitability study before returning. State Health Commissioner <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> is to decide the habitability question this fall. If <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> determines that the area is habitable, the state will have to assume liability for those who return, said former resident <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON>, now a Washington-based environmental activist. `` Will the deeds carry health warning labels?'' she said. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said environmental groups would sue to block resettlement, arguing that no one knows what levels of exposure to the chemicals are safe. If Love Canal is declared unsafe, it would set a precedent for people living around toxic waste dumps nationwide. The cost of relocating those people and cleaning those dumps would be astronomical, she said. The state, however, has vowed not to leave <LOCATION> Love </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> a vacant field as a symbol of environmental disaster. `` We have a vision of Love Canal as a usable landscape again,'' state Environmental Conservation Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jorling </PERSON> said recently. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said habitability decisions are being made across the country, though none are of the same magnitude as Love Canal. `` No situation is risk free,'' he said. `` You ca n't expect to be part of a highly developed, industrial society without weighing risks and ultimately living with them.''
</TEXT>
