<HEAD>A Chronology Of Events Leading to Partial Merger Of Detroit
Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are major events leading to Monday's approval of a joint operating agreement for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Free Press: May 9, 1986: The Free Press and News apply to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for a limited antitrust exemption allowing a cost-cutting combination of advertising, circulation and business operations while news and editorial departments remain separate July 23, 1986: The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s antitrust division recommends that Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> order a public hearing, saying the papers have not proved the need for a JOA. Aug. 22, 1986: A deadline for public comment is extended after Mayor <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, unions representing newspaper employees and some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> call for public hearings. Feb. 25, 1987: <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> says he will appoint an administrative law judge to conduct a hearing. May 29, 1987: Young and five unions obtain 30,000 pages of documents from the newspapers detailing cost-cutting efforts, loss projections and other items. June 1, 1987: The Free Press and News file written testimony saying the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 17 million in 1986, the News lost $ 12.7 million, and cost cuts or price increases would not save the Free Press. June 30, 1987: The challengers submit exhibits and testimony that the Free Press does not meet the test of a failing newspaper. Aug. 3, 1987: Administrative Law Judge <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Needelman </PERSON> begins a hearing in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Aug. 10, 1987: <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc.. Chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuharth </PERSON> testifies that the News will spend whatever is necessary to defeat the Free Press if a JOA is Aug. 12, 1987: <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Alvah </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> testifies that he will recommend closing the Free Press if a JOA is denied The hearing ends Aug. 24. Sept. 23, 1987: The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s antitrust division again recommends rejection of a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>, saying the papers failed to prove the Free Press is failing. Dec. 29, 1987: <PERSON> Needelman </PERSON> recommends that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> reject the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>. Jan. 10, 1988: `` I am worried. The Free Press could die,'' Free Press Publisher <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> writes in a front-page column. He asks readers to write, hundreds respond, the paper runs excerpts. Unions call the column a `` corporate propaganda advertisement mouthing the <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> line.'' Jan. 21, 1988: The <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> board votes to close the Free Press if a JOA is denied. Feb. 7, 1988: A mailers union drops its opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> in return for job protection, buyouts and severance pay. Feb. 11, 1988: <PERSON> Young </PERSON> drops his opposition, saying a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> is better than a one-newspaper town. Feb. 15, 1988: Unions representing press workers drop opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>. Feb. 16, 1988: Officers of Teamsters Local 372, the largest union, and unions representing typographers and photoengravers drop their opposition, leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> and the antitrust division as the remaining opponents. July 25, 1988: The Newspaper Guild Local 22 drops its opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>. Aug. 8, 1988: <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> approves the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>.
