<HEAD>Hunts' Lawyer: No Evidence of Silver Conspiracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A defense lawyer for <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> says there's no evidence that the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil tycoon and his two brothers were part of a plot to corner the world silver market nearly 10 years ago. <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and his two younger brothers are being sued for $ 150 million by a South American silver concern that claims the Dallas-based Hunts manipulated the world silver market between 1979 and 1980. In his closing argument to the jury Monday at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> noted that the Hunts lost more than $ 1 billion when the silver market collapsed in 1980. `` Where is the evidence they made a profit?'' <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> asked the six-member civil jury. `` If they were part of a conspiracy, it was one spectacular failure.'' The Hunts' <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and their three individual trusts, which control <ORGANIZATION> Penrod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drilling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, are in bankruptcy proceedings. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> said the Hunts were victims just like other silver investors. `` They believed too much in silver. They played and they paid,'' said <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Minpeco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, a mineral marketing company owned by the Peruvian government, claims in a federal civil action that the brothers _ <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 62; <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 59, who also has extensive real estate holdings, and <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 56, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> _ conspired unsuccessfully with several <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> businessmen to corner the world silver market. The trial before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasker </PERSON> began in February. Lawyers for Minpeco claim the Hunts and their Middle Eastern co-defendants were responsible for the sharp rise in silver prices from about $ 9 an ounce to more than $ 50 an ounce between September 1979 and January 1980. <PERSON> Minpeco </PERSON> had a large short position in the silver futures market, which meant it would make money on dropping silver prices and lose money on rising prices. <PERSON> Minpeco </PERSON> claimed it lost more than $ 100 million due to skyrocketing silver prices that fell back to about $ 10 an ounce in March 1980. Six financial institutions accused of participating in the alleged conspiracy have settled with <PERSON> Minpeco </PERSON> for a total of $ 64.6 million.
