<SECOND>BC-China-Selling Land,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Company First Foreign Firm to Lease Land in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Japanese company on Monday became the first foreign firm to `` buy'' land from the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government in public tender bidding. The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> news agency said <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> beat out five other firms to win rights to use a 12,900-square-meter -LRB- 139,320-square-foot -RRB- plot in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hongqiao </LOCATION> economic development zone for 50 years The report said the company will pay 104.16 million yuan -LRB- $ 28 million -RRB- for the land. It plans to construct apartment and office buildings, restaurants, stores and recreational facilities there. The selling of land-use rights is the latest, and one of the more controversial, measures taken by the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government to raise badly needed capital for economic development. Last month the city of <LOCATION> Shenzhen </LOCATION>, a special economic zone across the border from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, held <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s first land auction, with two Chinese companies winning the bidding for property development sites. Land in socialist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> technically all belongs to the state, but economists are now arguing that a market in land-use rights will bring in needed capital, bring about a more efficient use of land and speed up urban development. In the countryside, family farms that were rehabilitated with the start of agricultural reforms in 1979 usually have 10 - to 15-year contracts for farming a plot of land, but normally do not pay rent to the state In the cities, most Chinese factories and buildings occupy land without charge for unlimited periods. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature, paved the way for land-use sales last April when it amended the constitution to eliminate a prohibition against leasing land and added the sentence `` land-use rights according to legal regulation can be transferred.'' Some rural areas now allow residents not using their land to lease it to more ambitious farmers needing larger tracts. The government at the end of last year also named seven urban areas that may experiment with land-use sales: <LOCATION> Shenzhen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hainan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fuzhou </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Xiamen </LOCATION>. Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, however, stressed recently that public ownership will remain dominant in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. His statement appeared to be meant to assuage other party leaders worried that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was losing its socialist character with the emergence of thriving private enterprises and the selling of state land.
