<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to a private crop analyst's prediction of a sharp drop in corn and soybean production. The widely-followed analyst <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> pegged 1988 soybean production at 1.48 billion bushels, compared with actual production of 1.91 billion bushels last year. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> estimated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn production this year at 4.28 billion bushels, compared with 7.06 billion bushels harvested last year. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>'s numbers fell near the low end of other private estimates that have been released in advance of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s estimate on Thursday. In its July crop report, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> pegged 1988 soybean production at 1.65 billion bushels and corn production at 5.2 billion bushels. Although traders are eagerly awaiting the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report, which will be based crop conditions as of Aug. 1, the official numbers may have little market impact, said <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leow </PERSON>, an assistant vice president in charge of grain futures trading at <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` When the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> comes out with its number, people are most likely going to say it's too high because the survey was taken prior to the extreme heat we experienced last week,'' Ms. <PERSON> Leow </PERSON> said. In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 4 cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.80 a bushel; corn was 2 -LCB- cents to 3 cents higher with September at $ 2.99 a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with September at $ 2.74 a bushel; and soybeans were 3 -LCB- cents to 14 cents higher with August at $ 8.54 a bushel. Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .30 cent to .40 cent higher with August at 68.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .43 cent higher with August at 79.60 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August at 45.67 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to 1 cent higher with August at 33.15 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Monday.
