<HEAD>Wine Joins List of Australian Fascinations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WINSOR DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Crocodile </PERSON> <PERSON> Dundee </PERSON> might prefer to knock back a beer, but wine drinkers around the world are toasting their fascination with life Down Under by sipping more Australian wine than ever before. The explosion of interest in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s premium labels has resulted in some shortages and higher prices, as vintners struggle to keep pace with rising demand both here and overseas. Frost and hailstorms in some parts of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> prior to the 1988 vintage also have cut into supplies. `` Many Australians are drinking better quality wine,'' said leading wine writer <PERSON> Huon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooke </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Morning Herald. `` They want quality product, but much of that product is committed overseas.'' Contributing to the popularity of Aussie wines is the general bull market for things Australian, including actor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> and his carefree Crocodile Dundee character. Ironically, <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> can be seen in American television commercials, turning up his nose to fine wine tasting in favor of a frothy glass of beer. Also aiding the Australian industry is a trend away from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> wines after the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear disaster sparked fears of fallout across <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and scandals over illegal additives scarred the Austrian wine industry. Statistics show domestic consumers are drinking a better class of wine and deserting the taditional cask, or boxed wine. Wine sales in a country previously noted for its beer drinking have doubled over the past decade to 329 million liters last year. The increased popularity of premium wines has led to price rises of up to 30 percent locally and arguments from Australian retailers that producers should supply the local market ahead of the lucrative export markets of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The winemakers, looking to the future, are continuing to export enthusiastically. Australian wine is a competitor for Californian wine in many markets. It is particularly popular in northern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, accounting for 10 percent of all wine imports into <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> _ 7 million liters in the 1986-87 financial year. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> imported 4.5 million liters that year, and the figure is expected to rise considerably in 1987-88. The Australian Wine and <ORGANIZATION> Brandy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the government-funded marketing authority, said exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were up 62 percent last year to 2.7 million liters. `` Dollar for dollar we offer the best value quality wine available around the world,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuigan </PERSON>, managing director of the high-profile <ORGANIZATION> Wyndham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> reports that wine exports now total over 30 million liters annually, almost 10 percent of the total production. `` We are having great difficulty in meeting the demand for our wines,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, director of trading for Penfolds, which makes Grange Hermitage, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s world-class red wine. Penfolds is the largest winemaking group in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and the largest exporter. Grapes have been grown in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> since the first fleet of convict settlers arrived from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in 1788. The industry has been revolutionized over the past 20 years with the introduction of new technology, which led to the production of high-quality table wines. `` But there is a great deal of resentment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>,'' warned <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Anstee </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Lindemans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` Dealers feel they are being cheated, having made an initial investment in promoting Australian wine and being told <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> can not meet the demand.'' That echoes complaints at home. `` Countries like <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> are ready to service our consumers if the local industry ca n't meet local demands,'' said <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON>, a buyer for a bulk distribution company. Industry analysts predict the under-supply of premium products, which retail from around $ 5 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domestically, could last for three to four years. They also predict exports could rise to 25 percent of production within five years. But some experts in the industry believe the current premium shortage will be short-lived and has been aggravated by the unusual weather. `` We have better, cheaper land here than anywhere in the northern hemisphere and our production costs are less,'' said <PERSON> McGuigan </PERSON>. `` The current shortage, mainly of Chardonnay, is a temporary aberration. With the potential we have, we ca n't afford to stand still. We are the world's vineyard of the future.'' There are now some 500 wineries spread across the country. Among the premier wine-producing districts are the <LOCATION> Barossa </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Clare </PERSON> valleys and <ORGANIZATION> McLaren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vale </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Yarra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Hunter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. There are numerous other small areas where grapes are grown. Despite tight supplies, some winemakers believe now is the time to cultivate new customers. The <ORGANIZATION> Rosemount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, headed by former international winemaker of the year <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, has set up offices in <LOCATION> Ignacio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, and is currently exporting to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, among others. `` <LOCATION> Rosemount </LOCATION> is actively pursuing export markets,'' said managing director <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> Ryecroft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, believes there are still huge opportunities for Australian makers, particularly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> market. `` People overseas rarely know if they are eating Australian beef, or wearing Australian wool, but our wine is seen as an Australian product,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. `` It is an ambassador in a glass.''
