<FIRST>u f PM-DiscountRate 3rdLd-Writethru f0077 08-09 1018</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Discount Rate, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0077,1043</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 grafs White House comment after 2nd graf pvs;
inserts 2 grafs further after 8th graf pvs, ``I think ... Also
moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> announced today it is boosting its key bank lending rate from 6 percent to 6.5 percent, raising the possibility that other interest rates, including those on credit cards and mortgages, will go higher too. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement, said its decision `` reflects the intent of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to reduce inflationary pressures'' and `` was taken in light of the growing spread of market interest rates over the discount rate.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials were disappointed by the action. It was the first change in the central bank's discount rate since Sept. 4 and put the rate at its highest in more than two years. The increase, effective immediately, set the discount rate, which is the fee the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> charges to make loans to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial institutions, at its highest level since April 21, 1986, when it fell to 6.5 percent from 7 percent. Analysts had expected the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to tighten its reins on the money supply this week, but few were expecting an increase in the discount rate, which is the most dramatic move the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> can take. Most were expecting the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to push up the federal funds rate, the interest banks charge each other for overnight loans, by an eighth or a quarter of a percentage point from its current 7.75 percent. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, consulting firm, said he had not expected a discount rate increase from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> board, all appointees of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, until after the November elections. But, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> acted now rather than in the fall, when the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential campaign of Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is in full swing. `` I think the timing is very deliberate to do it before the Republican convention. That's sort of the kick off for the Republican political ampaign and raising the discount rate now may be seen as better than interrupting the campaign,'' <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, said the White House was `` naturally ... disappointed.'' But he also told reporters: `` The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> has had the task of trying to balance the resistance to inflationary pressures with maintenance of real growth in the economy. ... We believe the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> has been doing a good job of balancing these interests.'' The likely negative effects of the hike include pushing up the value of the dollar, which could slow the improvement of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. The dollar has been appreciating against foreign currencies since early this year and now stands at an 18-month high against the West German mark. It was the previous fall in the value of the dollar that shrank the trade deficit. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> also said that the increase now will likely make government borrowing this week more costly. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in its quarterly auctions, plans to sell $ 11 billion in 10-year notes today and $ 11 billion in three-year notes on Wednesday. Tuesday's discount rate increase marked the second under the reign of <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, who took over as <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> chairman a year ago. In September, the central bank boosted the rate from 5.5 percent to 6 percent, the first increase in three years. That move was also taken in response to inflationary fears, but was later cited by some analysts as a contributing factor to the October stock market crash. After the crash, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> pumped liquidity into the banking system. It loosened money supplies again in mid-winter, when rising business inventories raised concern that the economy was softening. Since then, however, government statistics have portrayed a strong economy and concern has shifted from recession to inflation. Tight labor markets in some areas of the country has been sparking worry about inflationary increases in wages. Some economists say steadily rising factory operating rates are likely to contribute to rising prices for manufactured goods. Last month, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said in congressional testimony that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> `` at this juncture might be well advised to err more on the side of restrictiveness rather than of stimulus.'' At that hearing, before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on July 13, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> had played down the prospect of an immediate increase in the discount rate after he was asked if he were worried about the growing gap between the discount rate and the federal funds rate, which had been increased in a series of small steps since late March. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> replied that `` current relationships are satisfactory'' and noted that the spread had been greater in the past. Too great a spread between the rates tempts banks to misuse the `` discount window'' by borrowing from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> and lending to other banks. In its statement today, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said it increased the discount rate in response to requests from <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> banks in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. As inflationary concerns have mounted in financial markets, other interest rates, including mortgage rates, have been increasing. The prime rate, the rate charged by banks to their most creditworthy customers, was raised by most major banks on July 14 from 9 percent to 9.5 percent, its highest since March 1986. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said a further increase in the prime rate could come this week. Among the recent signs of strength in the economy was the July unemployment rate, which at 5.4 percent was near its 14-year lows. In addition, the monthly trade deficits for April and May were the lowest in nearly three years. Prior to September, the last increase in the discount rate had come April 6, 1984, when the rate was boosted from 8.5 percent to 9 percent. The rate was then cut seven successive times, with the last reduction on Aug. 20, 1986, when it dropped from 6 percent to 5.5 percent, the lowest level in nearly a decade.
</TEXT>
