<FIRST>u f AM-Fed-Markets Bjt   08-09 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fed-Markets, Bjt,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Markets Cheer and Boo Discount-Rate Hike</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors dumped stocks and bonds Tuesday but the dollar rallied smartly against major foreign currencies after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> boosted its key bank lending rate a half percentage point for the first time since Black Monday. The increase in the discount rate, to 6.5 percent from 6 percent, was made `` to reduce inflationary pressures -LRB- and -RRB- ... in light of the growing spread of market interest rates over the discount rate,'' according to the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>. Many economists predicted other interest rates, including those on mortgages or home-equity loans, would rise as a result of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s credit tightening. And a few market watchers worried about the near-term effects on the already skittish stock market. The increase in the discount-rate _ the fee the central bank charges member banks for loans _ was the second since <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s helm a year ago. On Sept. 4, the central bank raised the rate for the first time in three years, to 6 percent from 5.5 percent. While last September's increase in the rate also was taken in response to inflationary fears, analysts later cited it as a contributing factor to the Oct. 19 stock market crash. `` I just hope history does n't repeat itself,'' said <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I do n't look for a market collapse but the cross-currents of the stock market are n't very favorable. It certainly is dangerous.'' On Wall Street, stock prices fell sharply in response to the announcement, with the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials losing slightly more than 28 points to 2,079.13. It had been down nearly 40 points late in the day. Bond prices tumbled while interest rates rose. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year issue was off about $ 10 per $ 1,000 face amount, while its yield jumped to 9.19 percent from 9.10 percent late Monday In foreign exchange, the dollar advanced strongly against major currencies. Higher interest rates make the dollar more valuable. The biggest increases came against the Japanese yen and West German marks. By late afternoon Tuesday, the dollar had broken through the psychologically important 135-yen level from Monday's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> close of 133.97, and to 1.92 marks from 1.90 Analysts had expected the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to tighten its reins on the money supply this week, but few were expecting an increase in the discount rate, which is the most dramatic move the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> can take. Tuesday's increase brings the discount rate to its steepest level since April 1986, when it fell to 6.5 percent from 7 percent. `` The -LRB- credit -RRB- markets have been screaming for a discount rate increase for quite some time; the surprise was in the timing of it,'' said <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>. `` Not only is the Republican convention coming up, but we're in the middle of a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> refunding,'' in which the government is auctioning off $ 22 billion in new three - and 10-year notes this week to pay off its old debts `` I do n't think inflation is any worse today than it was last year,'' said <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, defended the discount rate hike `` The economy has been doing well but inflation has ben creeping up,'' he said. `` It's the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s job to throw cold water on the economy when it starts overheating and that's what it appears to be doing right now.'' Among the recent signs of strength in the economy was the July unemployment rate, which at 5.4 percent was near its 14-year lows. Concerns about inflation have pushed interest rates higher in recent months. The federal funds rate, which is the interest on overnight loans between banks, has been on the rise. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reiners </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the yield spread between the fed funds rate and discount rate had been at its highest level in about a year. A month ago, major banks boosted their prime lending rates, a half percentage point to 9.5 percent from 9 percent. `` I would n't be surprised if we had another prime rate hike by Friday,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Resler </PERSON>, chief economist <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
