<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market fell deep into negative territory today in reaction to news that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> boosted its key bank lending rate, but equities managed to finish off their worst levels. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> announced shortly after the opening bell that it was hiking the discount rate a half a percentage point to 6.5 percent, its highest level in more than two years. Stock prices immediately headed south. An increase in the discount rate, which is the fee the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> charges for short-term loans to member banks, is the central bank's most direct way of pushing interest rates higher as a curb on economic growth Jumps in other interest rates, including those on mortgage rates and credit cards, are likely to follow. Analysts were cautiously optimistic that the market, which had been anticipating higher interest rates, could digest the hike in the coming days. They reasoned that with the dollar up sharply on the announcement, foreign funds will shift into dollar-denominated instruments like stocks and bonds. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Peroni </PERSON>, a technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Janney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, noted that volume, minus dividend-capturing strategies, was moderate and that there was no sign of any panic selling. A few investors took the opportunity to hunt for bargains and even considered the news somewhat positive. `` The feeling is that the sooner the medicine is administered, the quicker the patient will recover,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, vice president and technical analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. He also said the action enhance