<FIRST>u f AM-FishFarm Bjt   08-09 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Farm, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entrepreneurs Develop Indoor Fish Farm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUTZTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON> see the future of the American fishing industry in farmers' barns and abandoned inner-city buildings. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON>, co-founders of <ORGANIZATION> Fresh-Culture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, say they've developed a way to raise 40,000 pounds of fish a year in tanks fitting in 5,000 square feet of space. `` I think people will pay more for a top-quality product they feel safe with,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> said. Reports of medical waste and other pollution in the nation's waters has spurred increasing worries among consumer about the fish they buy, he added. The Fresh-Culture system, which sells for about $ 125,000, is the first to reduce energy costs enough to economically raise fresh-water fish indoors in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON> claim. Striped bass, salmon and other fish grown in the system's 15 cylindrical tanks can be sold to restaurants and fish markets to meet the growing demand for fish, they say. Increasingly health conscious Americans have been eating more fish in recent years. Consumption per capita has grown from 12.3 pounds in 1982 to 15.4 pounds last year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Herr </PERSON>, a program administrator with the state <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, said the technology used in the Fresh-Culture system is new. `` We definitely see that it will be able to be used by our <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> farmers that want to diversify,'' <PERSON> Herr </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON>, a 35-year-old former plant manager with <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said fish farming also could bring industry back to inner cities. `` You can put this in a burned out building they're selling for a dollar,'' he said. Fish farming itself is not new. Catfish have been raised in outdoor ponds for about 20 years. Trout also is `` farmed'' outdoors in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and elsewhere; and striped bass is raised in tanks in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and elsewhere. Unlike these systems, Fresh-Culture recirculates almost all the water in the tanks, said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON>, 36, who has been researching aquaculture for 10 years. It also costs little to heat, one of the main stumbling blocks of previous systems with recirculating water, he said. In a small building in <LOCATION> Kutztown </LOCATION>, a rural eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> town, <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON> and <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> are raising striped bass, trout and tilapia in one of their systems. They say they hope to begin selling their fish to restaurants in January. A 2 -LCB- horsepower motor pumps air to the 2,000-gallon tanks and pushes the water filters for them, while a computer monitors water temperature and heats the tanks overnight, when energy costs are lower, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> said. During a power outage, a backup gas-powered air pump is activated, he added. Trout and salmon require temperatures from 60 to 70 degrees, while striped bass and tilapia need 80-degree water, according to <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON> said fish can be produced in six months for about $ 2.50 a pound after start-up costs, with proper management, and sold for $ 5 or more to restaurants in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and elsewhere in the Northeast. <ORGANIZATION> Aquatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego-based </LOCATION> company, expects to harvest 650,000 pounds of striped bass this year from a fish farm in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hovanec </PERSON>, an assistant production manager. Unlike Fresh-Culture's system, Aquatic Systems has geothermally heated tanks and only recirculates some of the water, <PERSON> Hovanec </PERSON> said. `` I may be unnecessarily skeptical, but there are at least 20 or 30 people trying to get into striped bass,'' he said. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON> say they expect the skepticism. `` There are a lot of systems on paper,'' <PERSON> Fahs </PERSON> acknowledges. But they say they are confident their approach will attract customers. `` It's the freshest, non-polluted source of fish you can get,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorder </PERSON> said.
