<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading marketer of polymer grade propylene, announced plans Tuesday to expand capacity for the manufacture of the chemical at two <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> facilities. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> plans to expand capacity for the manufacture of polymer grade propylene at its Port Arthur refinery and <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bayou </LOCATION> olefins plant in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the company said in a statement. Polymer grade propylene is a high purity building block chemical used to make other materials such as polypropylene, which is extensively used in plastic automobile parts, toys, medical products and appliances. `` Chevron remains strongly committed to the polymer grade propylene business,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Olefins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Derivatives Division. `` The domestic and international propylene consuming businesses have been expanding rapidly in the past two years, especially polypropylene. This expansion assures that we will be able to keep pace with that growth,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>. The expansions, to be constructed in two stages, will add about 350 million pounds to the company's annual capacity to produce polymer grade propylene. The total capacity will be 1.3 billion pounds per year. The first stage is scheduled to begin in October and will boost capacity at subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Olefins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Derivatives Division plant at <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bayou </LOCATION> by about 20 percent to 800 million pounds by adding propylene splitting towers to its ethylene unit. The second stage, anticipated to begin during the fourth quarter of 1989, will boost capacity at subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arthur </LOCATION> refinery by more than 180 million pounds per year by adding a new propylene upgrading unit. The company said expansion at the two facilities will be complemented by installation of a new olefin splitter and export facility at <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Pascagoula </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, refinery, designed to separate and transport dilute propylene to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for further upgrading. In addition, the <LOCATION> Galena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> terminal of <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Warren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, situated on the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Ship Channel, will be modified to receive and transport this material to <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arthur </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bayou </LOCATION>.
