<FIRST>u f AM-ShippingRules     08-09 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shipping Rules,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Maritime Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> finding that industry rules for containerized ships unfairly discriminate against small cargo shippers was upheld Tuesday by a federal appeals court. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here said the maritime commission correctly ignored the rules' effect on labor-management relations when it found they improperly forced small shippers to employ unionized dock workers to handle their cargo. `` It is not the national labor policy to allow otherwise unlawful activity merely because an employer and a union have agreed to it in mandatory collective bargaining,'' a three-judge panel of the court said in a unanimous ruling. At issue are rules first negotiated in 1968 by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Longshoremen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the shipping industry that require unionized dockhands to load or unload cargo containers that pass through East Coast ports. The rules exempt manufacturers and large shippers that load cargo into containers at their own warehouses. But small shippers, whose cargo would not fill a single container, are forced to lease containers from the shipping companies and deliver their goods for loading at a unionized pier. The regulations were negotiated as part of the industry's efforts to introduce cargo containers, which can be unloaded from a ship into a railroad car or a flat-bed truck without being opened by dock hands The widespread use of containers has greatly reduced the number of longshoremen needed to unload ships and the rules were implemented to help the <ORGANIZATION> ILA </ORGANIZATION> cut the losses to its workforce. Last year, the maritime commission unanimously struck down the regulations, which were challenged by freight forwarders, trucking companies and handlers of small amounts of cargo. The commission's finding, however, was stayed while the ILA and the shipping industry appealed the decision. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammon </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brokers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forwarders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, hailed the court's decision, saying the rules amount to `` flagrant featherbeading ... that was just very damaging to import-export commerce.'' There was on immediate comment from the <ORGANIZATION> ILA </ORGANIZATION>, which is expected to appeal the decision to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The ruling could also become a bargaining chip in contract negotiations between the ILA and the shipping industry. The regulations require that merchandise placed on containers within 50 miles of a port by non-ILA workers had to be unloaded on the dock and placed into different containers before it was loaded on ships. The rules mean `` extra costs in delays and exposure to pilferage,'' <PERSON> Hammon </PERSON> said. Small cargo shippers have begun using Canadian ports to avoid the restrictions, resulting in less business for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> ports, he said.
</TEXT>
