<HEAD>Drexel Buys Staley Commodity Brokerage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investment banker <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will buy the commodities brokerage business of <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for an undisclosed amount, the companies said Tuesday. The sale of <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> marks the second divestment of a major <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> asset since early June, when London-based sugar refiner <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Lyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> completed its $ 1.5 billion acquisition of the <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meadows </ORGANIZATION>, Ill.-based company. <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> said when it set out to buy <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> that it would keep only <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s corn syrup refining business, the second-largest such operation in the nation. Tate & amp; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> sold <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s food-service business to <ORGANIZATION> Sysco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 700 million in June <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> established <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 to handle its own commodity brokerage requirements. The brokerage has since grown to become a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> with 26 seats on various commodity exchanges. The sale agreement calls for New York-based <ORGANIZATION