<HEAD>Detroit Newspaper Decision Keeps Competitive Questions Alive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs ``This means... to CORRECT `without' to
`with' in quote. Picks up 6th graf, William Keating...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The partial merger of two <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newspapers may not have an immediate impact across the industry, analysts say, but it could set the tone for the future with the market becoming more concentrated and the wealthiest media companies growing more powerful. The deal approved this week by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> brings together <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, in a deal four times larger than any joint operating agreement approved under the Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 While the move is designed to preserve two independent editorial voices in a big metropolitan market, some analysts and scholars still raise questions about the move's competitive impact. Critics charge the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> combination is a step toward further concentration of the industry where the trend is toward chain ownership and media conglomerates and where the number of independently owned papers is fading. `` This means that eventually there will be no city in the country left with competing papers and then pressure will be more immediate to wipe out the little competition that's left in the form of alternative papers, community papers and suburban papers,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brugmann </PERSON>, publisher of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guardian </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> that will oversee the merger, believes joint operating arrangements make good economic sense in an industry where second place often leads to financial failure. In the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> case, the advertising market share _ where a newspaper gets the bulk of its revenue _ had become so heavily weighted in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> that the Free Press could n't survive, <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said He said joint operating arrangements will continue to benefit the industry by saving newspapers too weak to survive on their own. `` Some newspapers will be saved by reason of a -LRB- joint operating agreement -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>. The danger in concentration, however, is that it could dilute competition by shifting power from the readers to media owners, who are in the position to charge higher prices for circulation and advertising. `` All we really know is that prices are going to go up,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON>, professor at <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who has studied joint newspaper agreements and approves of the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> arrangement. `` They'll be cutting their costs and increasing their revenues. It's the same thing that happens in any monopoly situation,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> predicted that <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newsstand prices, now among the lowest in the nation at between 15 cents and 20 cents per copy, could be raised to the industry average of 35 cents within the next few years. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenhoff </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, indicated Tuesday that prices will go up, but would not say when or by how much. `` What you have in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> are among the lowest newspaper circulation prices and advertising rates in the country,'' <PERSON> Lenhoff </PERSON> said. `` Both have been losing approximately $ 30 million a year. Logic would tell you that some changes are coming but it has not been announced to what extent.'' <PERSON> Lenhoff </PERSON> said an announcement may be forthcoming before the merger takes effect on Aug. 19. In 1920, 700 cities had competing dailies. Today, there are 22. Eighty percent of daily circulation is controlled by chains, and chains have begun to merge with each other. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>, who has absorbed other chains in recent years, is not a newcomer to joint newspaper agreements. The company is now an owner in eight of the 20 joint contracts and <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> is an owner in three. Under the partial merger approved Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION>, among the 10 largest in the country, will merge production, advertising and circulation departments for 100 years, while maintaining separate editorial and news departments. Although such a merger is illegal for other businesses under antitrust law, the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act granted newspapers selective exemption from the law if one of the newspapers is failing financially. The legislative intent was to preserve an editorial voice where one otherwise might be lost. Some analysts say the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> case could set a precedent for other large metropolitan newspapers. But others say there are few cities with competing papers ripe for such a merger. Of the 22 cities with separately owned, competing dailies, only a handful are potential candidates for joint agreements, including <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` There are so few markets where people would even want to get together and talk about it,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said.
