<HEAD>Batus Sweetens Offer For Farmers Group To $72 A Share From $63</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, struggling to win regulatory approval for a hostile takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, sweetened its buyout offer Tuesday to more than $ 4.9 billion from $ 4.5 billion in an apparent attempt to win a friendly agreement. Farmers, a major insurance holding company, stated late Tuesday that its board would give `` careful consideration'' to the latest offer. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> raised its offer to $ 72 cash a share for Farmers' 68.4 million common shares outstanding from the previous $ 63 a share bid, and conditioned the sweetened offer on the negotiation of a definitive merger agreement by Aug. 19. Farmers stock rose 12 -LCB- cents to $ 57.75 a share Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The sweetened offer was disclosed hours after the market closed. Farmers has resisted the overtures by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arm of British conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, since its initial $ 60 a share, or $ 4.2 billion, buyout offer in January. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> also has been attempting to win approval of the hostile takeover by the insurance commissioners of the nine states in which Farmers does business, with mixed success. Farmers noted three of the states _ <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ have rejected the takeover due to issues unrelated to the price offered by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> also has rejected the proposal, but that decision recently was overturned by a state court. Farmers is appealing the reversal. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, owns operations that include <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Williamson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and several retailers, led by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> Fifth Avenue.
